<HEADLINE> Arafat, Mubarak Meet on Hebron Stickers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat held an expanded
session of talks at the presidency headquarters here today when
sticking points still obstruct a deal on the partial Israeli
pullout from Hebron.
</P>
<P>
A team of senior Palestinian officials attended the meeting,
including Secretary of the PLO Executive Committee Mahmoud Abbas,
Minister of Planning and International Cooperation Nabil Shaath,
Minister of Local Government Saeb Erekat together with
Palestinian Ambassador here Zohdi al-Kuddrah and Arafat's advisor
Nabil Abu Redina.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival here this morning, Arafat said the
Palestinian-Israeli negotiations were facing difficulties.
</P>
<P>
"To overcome the difficulties, Egypt is exerting efforts and
the U.S. is giving a push," he added.
</P>
<P>
Describing the present situation as "quite sensitive and
critical," the Palestinian leader said it is necessary to come to
Egypt to brief Mubarak on the difficulties and to listen to his
advice.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, the first Arab country to make peace with Israel, has
been a strong advocate of the Palestinian cause and a pillar in
the Mideast peace process initiated in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The difficulties, he said, involve the issues of "hot
pursuit," the type of arms, buffer zone, and the resumption of
negotiations over pending matters, mainly redeployment and final
phase negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader will brief Mubarak on the latest
developments of the negotiations with the Israeli side and the
differences prior to his meeting with Israeli Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai this evening, said Arafat's advisor Nabil Abu
Redina, who accompanied him on the trip, before departure from
Gaza early this morning.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is also expected to meet with Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu Monday to clear their remaining differences,
according to the latest news from Jerusalem. The two leaders met
in Erez check point last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Negotiators from both sides will resume talks this evening on
the long-overdue deal on the partial Israeli troop withdrawal
from the West Bank city of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Abbas said Saturday that the deal
could be expected "within three to four days" if security
concerns are cleared.
</P>
<P>
The Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO) official told a
press conference here that Egypt is not in a neutral position to
give guarantees for implementing the deal nor might it attend the
signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
He said the two sides have agreed on the security arrangements
in Hebron in general, the airport, and the opening of the Shohada
and Hesba roads for Palestinians, but there are still some points
of disagreement between them.
</P>
<P>
A deal on Hebron would be the first major progress in the
peace process since the new Israeli government took office in
June and would open the door for peace talks on the Lebanese and
Syrian tracks.
</P>
<P>
Under the autonomy accords, the Israeli troop redeployment
from 80 percent of Hebron should be completed last
March. Netanyahu insisted on better security for the 450 Jews
living among 200,000 Palestinians in the city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
