<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Failed Parastatals Decree Causes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Some Nigerians may have fled
the country to escape trial under the yet-to-be-promulgated
failed parastatals decree designed to punish those responsible
for the failure of government enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The imminent decree may have also led some politicians to go
underground, the local newspaper Sunday Vanguard reported today,
but it did not give any details.
</P>
<P>
The decree is expected to be promulgated next month. It was
officially made public by the Head of State General Sani Abacha
in his October 1 independence broadcast.
</P>
<P>
Believed to have been put together by the Nigerian Economic
Intelligence Committee, the decree is aimed at punishing those
who have contributed one way or another to the collapse of some
government industries in the recent past.
</P>
<P>
The presidency has almost perfected the decree which may be
announced in next year's budget, said the paper, quoting a
committee source.
</P>
<P>
It is the hope of the Nigerian government that the decree will
help improve the performance of government enterprises because
the nation "needs a stong public sector for a private sector to
be effective", according to Sam Aluko, Head of the Nigerian
Economic Intelligence Committee.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
