<HEADLINE> UAE To Regulate Labor Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates
(UAE) will take new measures to regulate its market of immigrant
labors, local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Labor and Social Affairs Saif al-Jarwan was quoted
as asking his offices concerned to prepare plans for inspections
of companies and plants where immigrants have been employed.
</P>
<P>
The labor inspection plan came at the end of an amnesty
announced by the Interior Ministry in early July, which allows
violators of the country's immigration and labor laws to leave
without being punished.
</P>
<P>
The reports said that labor inspectors would conduct checks on
companies and plants on whether expatriate workers are working
for their original sponsors and on labour conditions, working
hours and salaries.
</P>
<P>
Each company or plant would be inspected at least twice a
year. Surprise visits are also expected to be carried out during
day or night working hours, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The UAE has been crowded with cheap but often illegal Asian
expatriate workers. In a drive started in early July, more than
200,000 foreign labors have peen forced to leave this oil-rich
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
