<HEADLINE> Roundup: Japan's Moderate Economic Recovery Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese economy has moved
out of a period of temporary slowdown and resumed a gradual upward
trend.
</P>
<P>
A recent government outlook said that the economy will continue
to recover in the immediate future, with its gross domestic
product (GDP) at a real 1.9 percent in fiscal 1997.
</P>
<P>
The projected growth is the lowest forecast ever but is still
higher than private-sector estimates and the projection by the
Paris-based Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development
(OECD). Most of Japan's private-sector economists put the figure
at below 1.5 percent and the OECD 1.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the outlook adopted by the cabinet of Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto earlier this month, the government said the GDP will
grow a nominal 3.1 percent in the year starting April 1.
</P>
<P>
During the latter half of fiscal 1996 ending March 31 and the
early fiscal 1997, the impetus provided thus far by government
spending will diminish, as additional funds allocated for
government investment are used up and private housing investment
peaks.
</P>
<P>
These factors will likely lead to a gradual rise in
deflationary pressures in the economy.
</P>
<P>
Forward indicators of government investment are already
beginning to deteriorate and, while demand for housing investment
is surging in advance of the scheduled increase in the consumption
tax, it is expected to reach a peak in the months ahead.
</P>
<P>
For the remainder of fiscal 1996, the economy is expected to
continue its expansion supported by the following three main
factors: first, the trend toward self-sustained recovery in a
broad range of sectors; second, the surge in consumption and
private housing investment prior to the rise in the consumption
tax, and a decline in external deflationary pressures as the
weakening of the yen brings recovery in exports and a slowing of
import growth.
</P>
<P>
As a result, real GDP growth in fiscal 1996 is expected to
reach 2.9 percent, versus 2.2 percent in fiscal 1995, according to
a Sanwa Bank forecast.
</P>
<P>
The Hashimoto cabinet gives top priority to the sweeping reform
of the economic structure, fiscal spending, the financial system,
social welfare and the bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
Though the consumption tax hike is prompting consumers to spend
before April, the government foresees a real 1.5 percent increase
in fiscal 1997 consumer spending on slowly rising employee income.
</P>
<P>
Consumer prices are projected to rise 1.6 percent, of which 1.5
percentage points will come from the tax increase. Wholesale
prices are expected to climb 1.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Private-sector capital investment will likely gain a real 7.1
percent, with recovery spreading from major manufacturers to
smaller businesses and nonmanufacturers.
</P>
<P>
Housing investment is forecast to decline a real 4.9 percent,
swinging from an estimated 11.5 percent gain in fiscal 1996.
</P>
<P>
Employment will gradually improve in step with the economic
recovery, with the jobless rate sliding to around 3.3 percent from
an estimated 3.4 percent in fiscal 1996, according to the
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
