<HEADLINE> British Universities Preparing to Charge Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Some of Britain's top
universities are collectively preparing to demand fees of up to
1,000 pounds (about 1,600 U.S. dollars) each year from
undergraduates.
</P>
<P>
The 17 institutions, which make up what is known as the elite
Russel group of universities, are expected to announce that
students starting from 1998 may have to make a contribution
towards their fees by the end of their three-year courses, the
Sunday Times newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The vice-chancellors from the Russel group decided to issue the
warning on introducing charges to students after a meeting later
this month.
</P>
<P>
Universities considering ending free higher education include
Birmingham, Bristol, Leeds, Liverpool, Manchester, Newcastle and
Imperial College and University of London in London.
</P>
<P>
Until now higher education fees have been paid by local
education authorities, which are reimbursed by the British
government.The new proposal stems from a financial squeeze created
by the Government's desire to increase the number of students in
higher education while reducing central funding.
</P>
<P>
In the current financial year, the Higher Education Funding
Council for England gave grants of 3.1 billion pounds (about 4.9
billion dollars) to 136 universities and colleges, a decrease of 4
million pounds (about 6 million dollars) from the 1995 grants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
