<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-ender: World Moves Toward Multipolarization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Contrary to a big power's wish
to dominate the world, the planet in 1996 moved steadfastly toward
multipolarization, with all major forces busy adjusting
strategies and building up strength so as to find optimal places
for themselves.
</P>
<P>
The move toward multipolarization this year was first of all
characterized by the setbacks suffered by the United States, due
to the strong opposition of the international community, in its
attempt to build a "monopolar world" for the 21st century, which
would be dominated by only one superpower.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. took two major moves in the year to maintain and
reinforce its position as the one and only superpower in the
post-Cold War world.
</P>
<P>
On the one hand, it strengthened the traditional military
alliance with its allies in the East and in the West to prevent
the emergence of possible rivals in Asia and Europe.
</P>
<P>
In the East, it strengthened the Treaty of Mutual Cooperation
and Security with Japan by expanding the scope of bilateral
security cooperation to include the entire Asia-Pacific region. It
also reinforced military cooperation with Australia.
</P>
<P>
In the West, the U.S. worked hard to push the eastward
expansion of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) to
include the allies and some republics of the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
On the other, the U.S. practiced hegemonism and power politics
throughout the world. Pursuing "unilateral interventionism," it
meddled in other countries' internal affairs under the pretext of
human rights, imposed economic and trade sanctions and launched
missile attacks on other countries.
</P>
<P>
With these hegemonist behaviors, the U.S. was condemned and
opposed by more and more countries, including its allies, leaving
itself in the most isolated position since 1990. This shows its
attempt to build a monopolar world is unpopular and the trend
toward multipolarization is irresistible.
</P>
<P>
Another feature of the world's move toward multipolarization
was that Europe, Japan and Russia showed a tendency for greater
independence and tried to become independent power centers in the
new world.
</P>
<P>
In order to become an equal to the U.S. in the 21st century,
the European Union went ahead with the integration process,
actively moved eastward and southward, and expanded its sphere of
influence in Asia, Africa and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
In particular, the EU reinforced the "European pillar" inside
NATO this year and France openly demanded a sharing of NATO
command. Some Western European countries contended with the
U.S. for the leadership role in the affairs of Europe, the Middle
East and Africa, and the EU held the first-ever Asia-Europe summit
meeting in March with 10 Asian countries without the
U.S. participation.
</P>
<P>
Japan, while quickening its pace toward becoming a political
and military power, demonstrated somewhat independence from the
U.S. on issues such as the U.S. military bases in Japan, the
Korean Peninsula and bilateral trade, hoping to eventually get rid
of U.S. control and become an independent pole in international
affairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
