<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961230.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-ender: World Moves Toward Multipolarization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Russia has been openly against the creation of a "monopolar
world." To this end, it opposed NATO's eastward expansion,
strengthened security cooperation with other republics of the
former Soviet Union and established a 21st century-oriented
strategic partnership with China.
</P>
<P>
Russia also pursued a flexible diplomacy in the Middle East,
Bosnia and other hot-spot areas, trying to provide a
counter-balance against Western countries. Meanwhile, Russia was
also developing its economy and envisaging military reforms so
that it could become a big power in the 21st century which would
stand on an equal footing with the U.S.
</P>
<P>
The third feature of the trend toward multipolarization was
that the developing countries were growing in strength and have
proved themselves to be a major force in international arena.
</P>
<P>
At the United Nations conference on human rights this year, the
developing countries joined forces and once again defeated the
attempt of Western nations to use human rights as a pretext to
interfere in the internatal affairs of other countries.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Assembly in November adopted a resolution with an
overwhelming majority, demanding that the U.S. lift its
30-year-long blockade against Cuba. Only the U.S. and two other
countries voted against the resolution.
</P>
<P>
The "backyard" of the U.S. was also on fire. At a meeting of
the Organization of American States in June, Latin American
countries passed a resolution rejecting the U.S. Helms-Burton law
which would punish the countries that maintain trade and economic
links with Cuba. This was something unprecedented in the
organization's 100 year history.
</P>
<P>
All this has shown that in the post-Cold War era, the
developing countries as a whole have become stronger both
economically and politically. They have become an important force
in pushing the world toward multipolarization.
</P>
<P>
The fourth feature of the course of multipolarization was the
sustained growth of the world economy, the economic globalization
and regionalization, and the economic pluralization.
</P>
<P>
This year, the world economy grew 3.8 percent, a record in
eight years. The world's three economic centers -- Western
Europe, North America and East Asia -- have grown in strength.
The five largest economies -- the U.S., Japan, Germany, China and
Russia -- were developing steadily. Subregional economic blocs
were flourishing in Southeast Asia, Latin America, Africa and the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
These economic forces have interwoven with each other at the
national, regional and global levels, promoting inter-dependence
and mutual penetration. They have provided a material foundation
and a driving force for the world's political multipolarization.
</P>
<P>
It will take a considerably long time before multipolarization
is completed. Throughout this process, there will be struggles
between domination and multipolarization, hegemonism and
anti-hegemonism, containment and anti-containment, control and
anti-control. These struggles could lead to regional conflicts,
tumults and even wars.
</P>
<P>
But multipolarization is an irresistible trend, which will lead
to a politically and economically more balanced world, thus
promoting the world peace and development into the 21st century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
