<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Opposition Wants Better 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The opposition Zimbabwe
Congress Party today said the government should take measures to
ensure that the coming year 1997 will not be marred by strikes
and corruption which brought suffering to Zimbabweans in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the party's President Kenneth Mano said
Zimbabweans in 1996 faced a number of hardships due to price
increases and the deterioration of the health system because of
strikes by medical personnel.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, 1997 should be a year of coming up with
constructive ideas which can improve our livelihood," Mano said.
</P>
<P>
He also queried whether the government would achieve its
goals of health and housing for all by the year 2000, when the
number of squatters is increasing around the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
