<HEADLINE> Ethiopia to Pay Better Price for Quality Coffee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The Coffee and Tea
Authority of Ethiopia announced today that it has plans to pay
coffee growers better price for quality item supplied to the
market.
</P>
<P>
Authority General Manager Isegaye Dirhane said farmers could
benefit from the sale of the cash crop picked at the right time,
avoiding the gathering of unripe, green beans.
</P>
<P>
Farmers as well as dealers engaged in coffee trade should pay
due attention to the quality and timely supply of the item to
come out winners and beneficiaries in the world market where the
number of exporter countries is increasing from time to time, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The authority, he said, has started supervision of coffee
supplied to the central market and at times sifts produce which
lacks quality even after the dispatch of the item from regions
with approvals for its quality.
</P>
<P>
Efforts will be made to raise the quality of coffee ready for
export if it fails to meet the standard, he added.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia is one of the major coffee producers and exporters in
the world. Coffee shares more than 50 percent of Ethiopia's
export, and 25 percent of the country's population are engaged in
coffee production, trade or related activities and it is the
source for 10 percent of government's revenue.
</P>
<P>
The decline in coffee price on the world market reduced the
earning of Ethiopia from coffee export last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
