<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Planning to Introduce Floating Prison </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The British Government
announced here today that it is planning to use a floating prison
ship to house hundreds of convicts in an effort to ease the
worsening overcrowding in conventional jails.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in an interview with the Independent Television News
earlier today, Britain's Home Office minister Anne Widdecombe said
that the jail ship named Resolution, which is to be moored off the
south coast port of Portland, is expected to house up to 500
prisoners from next month.
</P>
<P>
British prison services are facing ever increasing overcrowding
problems as the country's prison population has amounted to some
59,000.
</P>
<P>
Widdecombe rejected criticism from prison reformers that the
introduction of floating prisons was a throwback to the prison
"hulks" of the Victorian times.
</P>
<P>
"I have seen some rather stupid comparisons in the press today
with the hulks. It's nothing like that at all," she said.
</P>
<P>
She stressed that the ship prison was "modern" with a gymnasium
and "it has all the things that we could expect an ordinary prison
to have." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
