<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Reiterates Commitment to Mission in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The west African peacekeeping
force known as ECOMOG will remain committed to its mission in
Liberia and do all it can to facilitate the successful
implementation of disarmament of the Liberian warring factions.
</P>
<P>
According to Major-General Victor Malu, the force commander,
the ECOMOG will continue to take steps to eliminate anything that
would impede the success of the disarmament process, the News
Agency of Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
During a recent meeting in Monrovia, capital of Liberia, with
the new chief military observer of the U.N. Observers Mission in
Liberia, Malu noted that the peacekeeping force was dispatched to
the war-torn nation when the intensity of the killings became
intolerable and had no bearing to any objective of the fighters.
</P>
<P>
Before the ECOMOG's arrival, embassies of countries were
ransacked while Liberians in such embassies were brutally killed
to the extent that some of the embassies are yet to re-open
today.
</P>
<P>
He said the Liberian crisis has also posed danger to the whole
of the west African sub-region as it had the potential of
affecting the entire west African countries.
</P>
<P>
Since the civil war broke out in 1989, more than 150,000
people have been killed, leaving even more Liberians displaced or
as refugees in neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
As a result of efforts by the sub-region and the entire
international community, warring factions have agreed to cease
fire and more than 4,000 fighters have been disarmed since the
disarmament process began on November 22 this year.
</P>
<P>
The disarmament exercise will be completed at the end of
January next year and election of a new civilian government is
scheduled for May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
