<HEADLINE> Repatriation of Rwandan Refugees From Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Repatriation of Rwandan
refugees from camps in Ngara and Karagwe districts of Kagera
region in north-western Tanzania, has been completed, local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, over 500,000 refugees have been
handed over to Rwanda since the exercise started on December 14
this year and ended on Saturday when the last group of Rwandan
refugees crossed the Rusomo border post.
</P>
<P>
Government sources told the official Daily News in Ngara today
that an estimated 1,300 refugees could be still hiding in the
bush both in Karagwe and Ngara and pointed out that some hide
outs have already been identified by helicopter.
</P>
<P>
The government has declared that it is going to conduct a
house-to-house search after completion of the major operation to
ensure that all refugees are repatriated.
</P>
<P>
In Rwanda, meanwhile, Vice-Prime Minister Alex Kanyarengwe has
appealed to returnees from Tanzania not to take the law into
their own hands when reclaiming their property.
</P>
<P>
Radio Rwanda monitored here said that Kanyarengwe, who is also
Minister for Internal Affairs and Community Development, told the
returnees that they should follow the procedures through
government officials when reclaiming their houses. 
</P>
