<HEADLINE> Hebron Talks Continue to Clear Remaining Obstacles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators continued talks here today on removing the last
obstacles blocking a deal on Israeli troop redeployment in
Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian negotiator Jamil Tarifi said that difference on a
number of civil and security issues remained after today's
negotiations, which were held at a Jerusalem hotel. But he
meanwhile expressed the hope that an agreement could be reached
by Wednesday before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Amid reports of signing the Hebron deal within the week,
Palestinian Authority (PA) President Yasser Arafat is to meet
with Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai late tonight in a
bid to iron out all the remaining obstacles.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is visiting Egypt today to hold consultations with
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak on the Hebron talks. Israel
Radio reported that Mordechai today telephoned Mubarak to urge
him to use his influence on Arafat to help close the Hebron
talks.
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials said that after recent intensive
negotiations and the U.S. mediation, a Hebron deal was nearing
completion. But they added that some issues remained to be
resolved, especially on the security arrangements in the areas
close to the Tomb of Patriarchs, the shrine holy to both Jews
and Moslems.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is reportedly requesting conducting joint police patrols
at the Tomb of Patriarchs in Hebron, but Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu today firmly refused to accept this demand.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to Jewish students this morning, Netanyahu said that
Israeli troops would maintain "complete control" over the Tomb
of Patriarchs and that Jewish presence in Hebron would be
preserved forever.
</P>
<P>
"Anyone who tells you that we are leaving Hebron, he is
telling you a lie. We are there and we are going to stay
forever, for all time," Netanyahu said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Netanyahu said that he believed the
imminent Hebron deal would bring about more stability and
greater Israeli-Palestinian cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"We have arrived at security arrangements that I believe will
bring about more security, more stability ... and automatically
more cooperation between the Palestinians and Israelis in that
city (Hebron)," Netanyahu said.
</P>
<P>
The situation remained tense in Hebron pending the upcoming
Israeli redeployment. Two Molotov petrol bombs were thrown today
at Israeli troop outposts in the city, leading to the arrest of
several Palestinian suspects by Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
A Palestinian car was set on fire near a Jewish neighborhood,
but no clash was reported between the militant Jewish settlers
and Palestinian residents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
