<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-29 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Cancels Tel Aviv-Cairo Bus Line </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Israel's main public
transportation firm, Egged, ended today its regular service
between Tel Aviv and the Egyptian capital of Cairo, due to lack
of passengers.
</P>
<P>
According to an Israel Radio report, the firm lost 3,000
shekels (some 1,000 U.S. dollars) every time when a bus made the
12-hour Tel Aviv-Cairo trip, with only about 10 riders.
</P>
<P>
"The main reason is economic," Egged spokesman Ron Ratner
said. "In the last two years we have seen a steady decline in
passengers on a line that is expensive to run."
</P>
<P>
"There are simply less interest today (among Israelis) in
Egypt," he added.
</P>
<P>
The last Egged bus to Cairo left Tel Aviv today and will
return Monday, Ratner said, leaving Israelis with the
alternatives of flying or taking a chartered bus to Egypt.
</P>
<P>
However, Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, who
visited Egypt last week at the invitation of Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak, Friday called on Transportation Minister Yitzhak
Levy to act to stop the cancellation of the bus line.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai said the Tel Aviv-Cairo bus line is an expression
of peace between the two countries and a sign of normalization,
stressing that the peace with Egypt is strategic and each country
must make efforts to preserve and nurture it.
</P>
<P>
"The operation of the Tel Aviv-Cairo line is important, even
if the government will have to help Egged to maintain it due to
the small number of passengers," Mordechai said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
However, Ratner said the government turned down Egged's
request to subsidize the line, which was inaugurated in 1982,
three years after Israel and Egypt signed a peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of Israelis traveled on the line every week during
the 1980s, but Egged cut its service in recent years to just once
a week due to the decrease in passengers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961230.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-29 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Welcomes Russian Role in Solving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government
welcomed Russian active involvement in efforts for a solution to
the Cyprus problem, the Cyprus News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Yiannakis Cassoulides was quoted as
saying that Russia has played a significant role as a permanent
member of the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
President Glafcos Clerides will convey, through the island's
left-wing Akel Party General Secretary Demetris Christofias,
specific proposals on solving the Cyprus problem to the Russian
government, Cassoulides said, adding that there is possibility of
an official invitation to Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeni
Primakov to visit the island.
</P>
<P>
He also reaffirmed the government's wish for a coordinated
effort by the five permanent U.N. Security Council members
towards a Cyprus settlement.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, a spokesman for Akel Party has announced that
Christofias will travel to Moscow as a special envoy of President
Clerides to deliver a message to Russian Foreign Minister
Primakov on January 9.
</P>
<P>
The message is a reply to a letter sent by Primakov to
Clerides in October.
</P>
<P>
Russia has reportedly called for an immediate meeting between
the five permanent members of the Security Council and European
Union (EU) representatives to discuss practical ways to solve the
Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey sent troops
and seized the northern third of the island following a
short-lived coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-sponsored peace efforts have been going on for the
past 22 years, but so far no tangible results have been
achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
