<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Upbeat Economy Does not Lesson Job Worries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 29 (Xinhua) -- A growing number of Americans
believe the U.S. economy is in good shape. But the number
concerned about their own jobs has not changed significantly in
the last year.
</P>
<P>
The New York Tims today quoted figures of the Labor Department
to demonstrate the trend. The government figures show that the
number of people laid off in 1995, the most recent year for which
government data are available, rose to 3.47 million, nearly the
peak reached in 1992, right after the last recession. Through
November of this year, even after more than five years of economic
recovery, the number of layoffs announced by companies had
increased 14 percent from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Even as unemployment was extremely low, and with millions more
jobs created than were wiped out, people still have an anxiety for
their job security, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The new findings by the paper confirm that layoffs have become
a durable fixture of today's economy, occurring steadily in good
times and bad.
</P>
<P>
Three-quarters of all American households have seen a family
members, friend, relative or neighbor lose job since 1980.
</P>
<P>
In a poll by The New York Times earlier this month, 67 percent
rated the condition of the economy as fairly good or very good.
That was up from 51 percent in a similar poll conducted last
December.
</P>
<P>
Despite the improvement, economic insecurity persists at
virtually the level of a year ago, according to the new poll.
</P>
<P>
According to researchers, 10.1 million people were laid off
from 1993 through 1995 versus 6.7 million in 1987-89.
</P>
<P>
Economists also said that a fast-moving economy has created far
more jobs than it has destroyed in recent years. Since early 1992,
America has generated 12.3 million net new jobs. In 1995, the
number of new jobs created has outnumbered the ones wiped out at a
rate of 208,000 a month, leaving the country with much lower
unemployment rate than many countries in Europe.
</P>
<P>
However, of the workers laid off, only about a third could make
as much as or more than in their previous jobs. The rest were
working part time, were self-employed or were working full time
for less money than before, according to the newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961230.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-29 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Damascus Declaration Group Meeting Calls for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of the
Damascus Declaration group ended here today their two-day meeting
 by approving a document, calling for security and stability in
the region and closer pan-Arab cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The document approved by the foreign ministers of Egypt, Syria
and the six members of the Gulf Cooperation Council -- Saudi
Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Kuwait, Qatar, Bahrain and Oman
-- dealt with the latest developments in the Gulf, the Mideast
peace process and a joint Arab action framework, the Egyptian
Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Convened at a time of mounting tensions in the region, the
14th Damascus Declaration meeting reviewed Arab differences and
underscored the importance of respecting the sovereignty of Arab
countries.
</P>
<P>
The document released at the closing session condemned all
forms of terrorism and urged immediate measures against any
aggressions.
</P>
<P>
It voiced support for the UAE sovereignty over the three
islands of Greater and Lesser Tunbs and Abu Musa, over which the
UAE has a bitter dispute with Iran.
</P>
<P>
The meeting decided that the quadrilateral mediation committee
grouping the foreign ministers of Saudi Arabia, the UAE, Kuwait
and Oman would meet later in a bid to narrow the gap between
Bahrain and Qatar over a territorial dispute.
</P>
<P>
The document also welcomed developments in Iraq after the
execution of U.N. Security Council resolution 986 on the
oil-for-food deal, which was arranged as a partial lifting of the
international embargo imposed on Iraq after its 1990 invasion of
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the document urged Israel to keep its commitment to
peace and return occupied Arab land. Full normalization and
cooperation between the Arabs and Israel could only be realized
on Israel's abidance by the Madrid peace framework, said the
document.
</P>
<P>
It appealed to the Arab community to coordinate and unify
their actions in face of the Israeli intransigence and practices
detrimental to peace.
</P>
<P>
It called for adherence to the resolutions adopted by the
Cairo Arab summit held in June, which lent weight to underpinning
inter-Arab solidarity, establishing overall and just peace and
resuming peace overtures on all tracks in accordance with the
land-for-peace formula.
</P>
<P>
The document also called for enhancing economic, political and
security cooperation within the eight-member alliance and
reactivating the Arab League.
</P>
<P>
Damascus Declaration signatories have agreed to consolidate
the framework of joint Arab action, primarily enhancing economic
and technological ties to further their development.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also followed up on a number of economic
projects, previously approved in principle during the 13th
session held in the Omani capital of Muscat.
</P>
<P>
The Damascus Declaration, signed in the Syrian capital
following the 1991 Gulf war, calls for joint security and
military arrangements in addition to economic cooperation among
the eight signatories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
