<HEADLINE> Cold Snap Claims 7th Dead in Record Freeze </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The cold snap which descended
last week on France and other European countries claimed its
seventh victim Saturday night, as the temperature dropped to its
lowest in 30 years in the northeastern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
Charles Ziegler, a homeless man of 65 years old, died Saturday
night of hypothermia in a church house in Sarre-Union, Bas-Rhin in
eastern France, reported the Agence France-Presse (AFP).
</P>
<P>
A 29-year-old woman miraculously survived after she was found
in a forest in Saone-et-Loire this morning, her temperature having
dropped to 29 degrees.
</P>
<P>
The average temperature of northeast France dropped to minus 16
degrees centigrade Saturday night, with Strasbourg froze in minus
15 degrees, two degrees lower than the record cold registered on
December 28, 1962.
</P>
<P>
In Paris and its suburbs, the thermometer stayed from minus
eight to minus 10 degrees centigrade, against minus 11 to minus 14
degrees registered on December 28, 1962.
</P>
<P>
The southern city of Toulouse had the coldest day since 1947
Saturday with minus three to minus six degrees.
</P>
<P>
The Mediterranean island of Corsica had its first snow in 10
years, where the ceiling of a supermarket near Bastia collapsed
due to the weight of the snow, and electricities were cut in
several places by the snowfall.
</P>
<P>
The western coast of France was also not spared from the cold,
with temperature ranging between minus eight degrees and 10
degrees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961230.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Expects Most Refugees to Return Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, December 29 (Xinhua) -- With peace and stability
being firmly established in Bosnia, more and more refugees in
Yugoslavia would be ready to go back to Bosnia in 1997, a Serbian
refugee official said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Bratislava Morina, President of the Serbian Refugees
Commission, said the commission planned to sign a memorandum with
Bosnian Serb entity Republka Srpska in January to facilitate the
return of refugees.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum would be coordinated with a plan of the U.N.
High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), and set a two-year period
to complete the return of refugees, Morina said in a statement to
Tanjug news agency.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia has housed more than 600,000 refugees fleeing from
Bosnia and Croatia from 1991 to 1995, which was a heavy burden to
Belgrade both economically and socially.
</P>
<P>
Due to unwillingness of political leaders in Bosnia and
Croatia, the repatriation process has been going on rather slowly.
UNHCR Belgrade Bureau has said it has managed to send back about
1,000 refugees back to Bosnia and Croatia this year.
</P>
<P>
Morina said she expected more refugees would like to go back to
their homes in Bosnia and Croatia now than six month ago, when
only 49.2 percent said at that time they wished for a
repatriation.
</P>
<P>
More refugees would opt for a return with the stable peace and
political circumstances in Bosnia, and normalization of relations
between Yugoslavia and Croatia.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia normalized relations with Croatia in August of this
year and gained a mutual recognition with Bosnia two month later,
thus paving a way for a safe repatriation of refugees from
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"Yugoslavia wants to solve the problem of about 600,000
refugees permanently," the refugee official said, adding the
memorandum would specify principles for the return of refugees,
specifically for the first 50,000 returning to Republika Srpska.
</P>
<P>
Morina noted that Yugoslavia, which comprises of Serbia and
Montenegro, was exhausted after the four-year U.N. sanctions, and
was unable to provide a permanent solution to so many refugees,
the more so as international humanitarian organizations had not
provided funds for such a solution.
</P>
<P>
Fearing possible conflicts in the future or with their houses
under the former enemy's territories, many refugees have chosen to
stay in Yugoslavia and be reintegrated into local community
gradually, according to investigation of UNHCR officials based in
Belgrade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961230.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-29 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cafe Explosion Wounds 20 Algerians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 29 (Xinhua) -- At least 20 Algerian citizens
were wounded, some seriously, in an explosion at a cafe at about
10:30 a.m. (10:30 GMT) today in the southeast Algiers suburb of
El Harrac, according to media reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
So far, no organization has claimed responsibility for the
attack.
</P>
<P>
A statement to this effect was released today by the Algerian
Public Security Administration.
</P>
<P>
The Administration did not say whether the explosion was
caused by a booby trapped car or a time bomb, although the latter
possibility is more probable as it took place inside the cafe.
</P>
<P>
Algeria witnessed over the past week several explosions. On
December 21 and 22 three explosions had taken place in downtown
Algiers, the capital, killing and wounding a number of civilians.
</P>
<P>
On December 24, five Algerian citizens died and 15 others
injured by the explosion of a booby trapped car in the town of
Bleida, some 50 kilometers south of the capital.
</P>
<P>
Again on December 25, a bomb exploded in the capital city
killing one Algerian citizen and wounding 13 others of whom 6
were in critical conditions.
</P>
<P>
On December 26, a booby trapped car exploded in the capital
resulting in the death of 7 persons and the injury of over 70
others.
</P>
<P>
This brings to more than 240 the number of civilian victims
hit by explosions since the beginning of December.
</P>
<P>
Algeria has been plagued by violence between militants and
government security forces that has left more than 60,000 people
dead in the country. The insurgency started in 1992 when the
government canceled parliamentary runoffs the Islamic Salvation
Front was expected to win. The insurgents seek the establishment
of a government based on Islamic law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
