<HEADLINE> Roundup: Hashimoto to Tackle Reform, Security in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto
faces a tough time when the Japanese Diet (parliament) convenes in
late January, with the leading opposition New Frontier Party (NFP)
 likely to pounce on his cabinet over a series of bureaucratic
scandals.
</P>
<P>
Whether Hashimoto, who heads a minority government formed
exclusively by his Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), will survive
all the challenges remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
The LDP made some gains in the October 20 election for the
House of Representatives, but does not have a majority in both
houses of parliament. It must rely on its two smaller political
allies -- the Social Democratic Party (SDP) and new Party Sakigake
-- for support.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto has vowed to undertake sweeping reforms in five
fields -- administration, economic structure, the financial
system, social security structure and the budgetary system.
</P>
<P>
His promise to realign Japan's 22 government ministries and
agencies to streamline Japan's bureaucracy by the start of 2001
will start with reform of the powerful Finance Ministry, following
the ministry's poor handling of the massive bad loans scandal
involving housing loan firms, widely known as "jusen."
</P>
<P>
The LDP, the SDP and Sakigake, which worked out a Finance
Ministry reform plan earlier this year, hope a bill on their
reform blueprint will be discussed during the upcoming Diet
session.
</P>
<P>
Although talk of carrying out administrative reform is
conducted in loud tones in the nation, cozy relations among
politicians, bureaucrats and the business community remain
uncorrected.
</P>
<P>
Apart from being beset by knotty domestic issues, the Peru
hostage crisis is posing severe test of leadership for Hashimoto.
</P>
<P>
With more than 80 people still being held hostage in the
Japanese ambassador's residence in Lima, crisis management has
been added to the list of priority tasks Hashimoto must address
during his second term in office.
</P>
<P>
By autumn 1997, Japan will complete a review of guidelines for
action by the nation's armed forces in cooperation with the U.S.
"in case of emergency" in the East Asian region.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto must also weigh up the political and diplomatic
fallout from his decision -- by next summer -- whether to accept a
U.S. proposal to jointly develop an advanced antimissile system
for "Theater Missile Defense."
</P>
<P>
The issue of strengthened military cooperation with the United
States, which goes to the heart of a decades-long constitutional
debate over the use of the armed forces, goes in tandem with the
political hot potato Hashimoto must grapple with over
U.S. military bases in Okinawa Prefecture.
</P>
<P>
Although Hashimoto has managed to ease Okinawa's objections to
the huge U.S. military presence in the prefecture, the bases issue
is hardly over.
</P>
<P>
The Hashimoto administration must select a site in the
prefecture to relocate a heliport used by U.S. marines at the
Futumma Air Station, one of the military installations in Okinawa
the U.S. government has promised to return to Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
