<HEADLINE> China Opts For Market-Oriented Financial Leverage In 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- China made a giant step down
the road of macro-economic controls this year by resorting to
market-oriented leverage like interest rates, and is expected to
do more next year.
</P>
<P>
"In terms of macro-economic financial controls, I must say that
1996 has been a year when the country took a series of steps to
shift policy to indirect market-driven means from direct means
like administrative orders," said an official of the People's Bank
of China (PBC), the central bank.
</P>
<P>
This year, China's effort to use so-called indirect means for
macro-economic financial controls started with boosting the bill
re-discounting business with the Bill Law on January 1. The bill
discounted and re-discounted reached a total of 195.5 billion yuan
(about 23.5 billion US dollars) and 116 billion yuan,
respectively, between January and November.
</P>
<P>
Bill re-discounting has played a positive role not only in
curbing the note issuing growth, but in improving the distribution
of bank credit and improving the industrial structure, Li Yang,
director of the Finance Research Center of the Chinese Academy of
Social Sciences, told Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
Other indirect financial controls China adopted this year
included starting market operations in treasury bonds on April 9,
cutting interest rates on bank deposits on May 1 and August 23,
using an asset-to-liability management mode to replace the
prevailing credit quota system in commercial banks on a trial
basis, withdrawing the central bank's discount loans to commercial
banks to offset the inflationary pressures caused by
rapidly-growing foreign exchange reserves, and other measures.
</P>
<P>
"The traditional macro-economic financial control mechanism
cannot cope with the development needs of a market economy in
China," said Tao Liming, deputy director of the International
Finance Research Institute of the Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
Economic restructuring and the difficulties that the central
bank has met with in financial controls since China began its
reform and opening-up policy in the late 1970s have prompted China
to look more for indirect means than for direct means, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The central bank's active and flexible use of indirect
macro-economic financial controls like interest rates and open
market operations has successfully limited the money supply and
guaranteed stable growth in the national economy by avoiding an
excessive tightening or loosening of the credit supply," Tao
noted, saying that the effect of administrative controls on credit
under a planned economy was very poor.
</P>
<P>
"A common scenario at that time was that 'rigor mortise' used to
set in when the credit supply was tightened and chaos followed
when it was loosened," Tao sai, "and ultimately, there were wild
ups and downs in economic growth."
</P>
<P>
The increased use of indirect financial controls can help
accelerate China's pace of opening its financial sector to foreign
competition, he said.
</P>
<P>
It also indicates that the PBC's ability to formulate and
implement monetary policies independently has improved and that
its status as a central bank has been increased, both experts said.
</P>
<P>
In another move to exercise macro-economic financial controls
with market-based leverage, the PBC is expected to cut the reserve
ratio for commercial banks in the first half of next year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
