<HEADLINE> HK to Bid for '99 Short-course World Swimming Champ </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Obviously inspired by its
success of staging the World Cup short-course swimming meet for
the last three years, Hong Kong has officially applied for hosting
the 1999 World Short-course Swimming Championships.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held here Monday for Epson Swimming World
 Cup Hong Kong '97, which is the opening leg of the eight-leg
World Cup series next year, officials of the Hong Kong Amateur
Swimming Association (HKASA) said the association had faxed
necessary documents to FINA, the sport's world governing body.
</P>
<P>
A. de O. Sales, president of the HKASA, said that the Kowloon
Park Indoor Swimming Pool, site of the World Cup competitions
here, has witnessed two new world records and other world-class
performance. "This proved that this is really a fast pool," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He confirmed the HKASA had decided to bid for the '99 world
short-course championships.
</P>
<P>
Ronnie Wong, secretary of the HKASA, said the association's
ability had been proved by its successful hosting of the World Cup
meets in the past.
</P>
<P>
The '97 World Cup meet here next month would provide one more
chance to prove that Hong Kong is suitable to stage world
championships, he said.
</P>
<P>
But Wong admitted that Hong Kong has a 50-50 chance to succeed
in the bid. Among other bidders are cities of Britain, Canada and
Japan.
</P>
<P>
Wong said that if Hong Kong is given the right, the world
championships will be held in the Kowloon Park Indoor Swimming
Pool. But the spectators' stand shall be expanded to 3,500 seats
from the current 1,700, he said.
</P>
<P>
To bid for a short-course, instead of a long-course or
Olympic-standard, world championships is more practical and
realistic at present for Hong Kong, Wong said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
