<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Taking Steps To Open Its Financial Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Chinese and foreign financiers
welcomed the central bank's decision today to allow overseas bank
branches to deal in Renminbi yuan, calling it a substantial move
in opening up its banking sector.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai branch of the People's Bank of China (PBC)
announced that Citibank, the Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corp.,
the Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi, and the Industrial Bank of Japan
have been given approval by the head office of China's central
bank to move their Shanghai branch offices to the city's Pudong
New Area and to deal in the local currency on a trial basis.
</P>
<P>
"Allowing foreign banks to do business in Renminbi yuan marks a
major step in the country's effort to open its financial sector to
overseas competition," a PBC Shanghai official noted.
</P>
<P>
The four banks' new business in yuan includes accepting
deposits, extending loans, providing guarantees, and investing in
Chinese treasury bonds and financial bonds, according to today's
announcement.
</P>
<P>
Henry Luo, assistant to the president of Citibank's Shanghai
branch, told Xinhua that the latest move "indicates that Shanghai
is taking one substantive step closer to its ambition of being an
international finance center."
</P>
<P>
"This is one of the two major efforts China has made this year
to open its financial sector wider," Luo said, referring to the
earlier move of making the yuan convertible this month.
</P>
<P>
As China allows overseas banks to deal in yuan, it will
withdraw its preferential treatment of them, such as tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
"In this sense, I must say that being allowed to do yuan
business is both an opportunity and a challenge to us," Luo said.
</P>
<P>
Li Yang, director of the Finance Research Center of the Chinese
Academy of Social Sciences, told Xinhua that the latest move
demonstrates that China's economic and financial situation is
stable, and "in some sense, it's the real beginning of China's
financial market opening to the rest of the world."
</P>
<P>
He urged Chinese banks, especially state-owned ones, to improve
their operations in order to stand firm against growing financial
competition.
</P>
<P>
"Competition between Chinese and overseas financial
institutions will become more intense and our banks must improve
themselves," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ever since Hong Kong's Nanyang Commercial Bank became the first
overseas bank to set up a Chinese branch in Shenzhen in 1981, the
number of overseas financial banking institutions has grown fast -
by August, there were 137 overseas bank branches in 17 Chinese
cities.
</P>
<P>
If they don't have approval from China's central bank, the
branch banks are restricted to foreign-exchange business only, and
clients are confined to foreign-funded enterprises in China,
people from overseas, or those from Hong Kong and Macao.
</P>
<P>
On July 1, overseas branch banks were allowed to trade in
foreign exchange with overseas-funded enterprises for the first
time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
