<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lu Ping Confident About Hong Kong's Future (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
When asked about the obstacles the Preparatory Committee has
met in its preparations for the Hong Kong SAR, Lu said the work
was unprecedented and full of challenges, and "needs the joint
creative efforts of all of us," and that there are still various
interferences and troubles.
</P>
<P>
"Some persons have different views about establishing the
Provisional Legislative Council and attempted to impose pressure
on us using international force," he said, but that no one can
stop the advancement of history.
</P>
<P>
In looking back on 1996, Lu said that "an important experience
for use overcoming difficulties, to eliminate interferences, and
work well lies in our efforts to resolutely implement the work
principle of relying on the Hong Kong people and gearing to their
needs as put forth by President Jiang Zemin, and bring them fully
into play, allow them to be involved in the transition through
varied channels and in various ways," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the future work of the Preparatory Committee, Lu said, "It
does not mean that we can relax just because the first Chief
Executive-designate and the Provisional Legislative Council of the
Hong Kong SAR have been selected.
</P>
<P>
The Preparatory Committee has set up a working panel for the
first Legislative Council, which will study specific methods of
establishing the first Legislative Council of the Hong Kong SAR,
he said, and that many issues concerning Hong Kong laws, the
economy, and people's lives are yet to be studied.
</P>
<P>
The Preparatory Committee will report on progress in the
preparatory work at the National People's Congress to be held in
March.
</P>
</TEXT>
