<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-30 14:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regional Factors Slows Jordan's Economy in 1996: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Regional factors slowed Jordan's
economic growth in 1996 to 5.3 percent, a fall from 6.6 percent in
1995, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The decrease in the growth rate was mainly attributed to
regional factors, which are beyond Jordan's control, according to
a signed article carried in Jordan Times, the kingdom's sole
English language daily.
</P>
<P>
The election of Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Natanyahu in
May brought about "a significant level of apprehension," and as he
began to fulfill his campaign promises, investment began to drop
in both Israel and Jordan, Yousuf Mansur, a Jordanian expert in
economics, said in the article.
</P>
<P>
Had Netanyahu not won the elections, a better regional
investment climate would have been sure to emerge, said Mansur.
</P>
<P>
Investment in Jordan has decreased slightly from the previous
year with imports representing 4.6 percent of the gross domestic
product (GDP), compared with 3.7 percent in 1995, the article said.
</P>
<P>
Per capita debt was 1,455 U.S. dollars in 1996, down from
1,467 dollars in 1995, it said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign grants amounted to 191.3 million Jordanian dinars
(about 273.3 dollars), a sum that was not as high as one would
wish and which is likely to decrease by 18 percent in 1997, the
article noted.
</P>
<P>
Unemployment decreased from 15 percent to 13 percent as
foreign labor markets opened to the Jordanians, according to the
article.
</P>
<P>
There are opportunities for Jordan to develop its economy in
1997 as Jordan is striving to sign a free trade agreement with the
European Union (EU) and has applied for accession to the World
Trade Organization, Mansur concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
