<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Vows to Tackle Russia's Most Complicated Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
said today he is ready to tackle the country's most complicated
problems.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, who returned to work in the Kremlin last week after a
heart by-pass operation on November 5, said "the achievement of
concord and reconciliation is the task for next year."
</P>
<P>
Speaking during a New Year's Eve interview with Russia's three
leading news agencies -- Itar-Tass, Interfax and Ria Novosti --
Yeltsin said, "Our actions in the economy, politics and the
intellectual sphere must facilitate the overcoming of differences
among the Russian people," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Russian leader went on to say, "Specific action for the
good of the people is the most important of all" in the coming new
year and he expected 1997 to be "more successful" for Russia.
</P>
<P>
Summing up the most important achievements of the past year,
Yeltsin singled out three major events: the presidential and
local-government elections, peace in the breakaway region of
Chechnya, and success in curbing inflation.
</P>
<P>
"Of course, the situation in the country remains complicated.
We will make efforts in the new year to change things for the
better," the Russian President said.
</P>
<P>
Asked about 1996 in personal terms and what he was expecting
next year to bring, Yeltsin said, "This year had been difficult
for me, because of the elections, my heart disease and the surgery.
</P>
<P>
"Now I am ready to grapple with the most complicated problems
facing Russia...I should make up for the lost time." 
</P>
</TEXT>
