<HEADLINE> Lu Ping Confident About Hong Kong's Future (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
When asked to comment on a series of remarks that opposed the
provisional legislature made by the British side on a number of
occasions in a vain attempt to internationalize the Hong Kong
question, Lu noted it is known to all that it is the British said
which unilaterally undermined the "through-train" arrangements,
and that the Chinese side made a decision to set up the
Provisional Legislative Council in order to ensure Hong Kong's
stable transition and proceed from Hong Kong's overall interests.
</P>
<P>
Some British oppose the Provisional Legislative Council, and
have said that the matter will have to be handed to be adjudicated
by the international courts, and this is futile, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said before its return, Hong Kong is a matter that concerns
China and Britain and, after 1997, Hong Kong affairs will be
China's internal affair, and that any attempt to internationalize
the issue will be unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the British side will take the whole situation
into account and look toward the future during the last half year
of rule, and shoulder the responsibility of a stable transition
and greet 1997 with a cooperative attitude," he said.
</P>
<P>
Lu said the new year will be an inspiring year, and that the
principle of "one country, two systems" initiated by Deng Xiaoping
will become a reality, and the aspirations of several generations
of Chinese will come true, and this is a great event for the
Chinese nation.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that in the coming year, the people of
Hong Kong will, as always, make an effort to build a bright future
for Hong Kong under the banner of loving the country and loving
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Lu concluded by wishing the people of Hong Kong and Macao a
happy new year and happiness and brisk business.  
</P>
