<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Standing Committee On HK Garrison Law  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The law on stationing troops
in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) adopted by
the 23rd Session of the Eighth National People's Congress (NPC)
Standing Committee was described today as being "another important
law to be implemented in the Hong Kong SAR following the Basic
Law."
</P>
<P>
The comment came from Zhou Nan, Wang Shuwen and Tsang Hin Chi,
members of the NPC Standing Committee, in interviews with Xinhua
today.
</P>
<P>
The three said they agree that, judging from the specific
provisions, the Garrison Law conforms to the Basic Law, and
demonstrates the spirit of "one country, two systems", which is
significant in safeguarding state sovereignty, unity,
reunification, and territorial integrity, and maintaining Hong
Kong's long-term stability, prosperity, and safety.
</P>
<P>
It took four years to draft, revise, and approve the law, and
the group who drafted the law read a total of 31 volumes of Hong
Kong Laws in English, more than 100 copies of cases in Hong Kong,
and translated one million words of materials, and studied British
jurisprudence and other countries' military legislation.
</P>
<P>
In the process of drafting the law, the opinions of the people
of Hong Kong were solicited in various ways, and the Eighth
National People's Congress Standing Committee repeatedly discussed
the draft of the Garrison law.
</P>
<P>
"This is a complete, systematic, and mature law for
administering the army," they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
