<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Press Association Boycotts Israeli Fair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The Jordan Press Association
(JPA) has urged the press establishments and reporters not to
cover an Israeli trade fair scheduled to be held here in January,
a local press report said today.
</P>
<P>
The call was announced by the JPA Sunday to all the press
organizations in the kingdom in a signed memo which said the
boycott stemmed "from an overwhelming national rejection of the
idea" of holding such an event in Jordan, the local daily Jordan
Times reported.
</P>
<P>
It cited "the Israeli authorities' disregard for Arab rights,
escalation of criminal practices against the Palestinian people
and aggression on southern Lebanon" as the basis for its calls to
boycott the event.
</P>
<P>
"The Jordan Press Association is asking you to boycott the
exhibition, refrain from publishing anything about the event or
visiting it yourself," said the memo. It also urged the press
establishments and journalists to ask the public to be committed
to a "total boycott" of the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
An unidentified JPA board member said the decision to issue
the call was taken at a board meeting Sunday after the organizers
of the exhibition sent invitations to press establishments and
journalists to cover the event after obtaining special passes.
</P>
<P>
"The JPA board does not intend to take any punitive action
against its members who cover the event," said the board
member. He pointed out that reporters, including those of the
state-owned media, had no choice but to report on the exhibition
if asked to do so by their employer.
</P>
<P>
"It will be unfair for the JPA to adopt any action against
those who can not make their own decisions," he added
</P>
<P>
The trade exhibition will be the first Israeli exhibition to
be held in Jordan after the kingdom and the Jewish state signed a
peace treaty in October 1994.
</P>
<P>
The organizers of the exhibition said they are going ahead
with the project despite opposition from Jordanian political
activists and businessmen associations.
</P>
<P>
However, Jordanian opponents of normalization of ties with
Israel have reportedly set up a "national Jordanian committee for
canceling the Israeli trade fair," and are threatening Jordanians
who attend the fair with blacklisting.
</P>
<P>
Ahmad Obeidat, former prime minister and chief of the
committee, said Saturday that the group comprising people from
the Parliament, political parties, trade unionists, women's
groups and human rights organizations, would create a blacklist
of participants, including reporters who will cover the event.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties argued that the trade fair would only
serve Israel's business interests of getting into the Arab
market.
</P>
<P>
Opposition force in the Parliament, led by the Islamic Action
Front (IAF) party, has called on the government to cancel the
Israeli exhibition.
</P>
<P>
Business organizations argued that the time is not opportune
for Israel to hold a trade fair in Jordan, given the stalled
implementation of the Israeli-Palestinian agreements.
</P>
<P>
They also said that a strong message should be sent to the
hardline Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Natanyahu that he could
not hope for economic benefits while he continued to refuse to
acknowledge and respect Palestinian rights.
</P>
<P>
According to Jordan Times, the government asserted that trade
fairs, whether Israeli or otherwise, were the affairs of the
private sector and pointed out that the Jordanian-Israeli peace
treaty provided for trade ties between the two countries. Thus,
its officials said, the government left it for the private sector
to make the decision as to develop whatever trade relations with
Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
