<HEADLINE> MOFTEC Official on Economic Ties Across Taiwan Straits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The year 1996 saw a U-turn in
the development of economic and trade contacts between the two
sides of the Taiwan Straits, the latest issue of "Outlook"
magazine quotes Wang Hui, an official with the Ministry of Foreign
Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC), as saying.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade increased in the first two months of the year,
then began to decline and hit its lowest level in June. In July,
it began to increase slightly, wang said in an interview with
Outlook.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that the "Two Chinas" and "One China, One Taiwan"
policies pursued by the Taiwan Authorities caused a tense
situation between the two sides of the Straits, which affected
cross-the-straits trade and economic exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Owing to artificial obstacles and political factors, the volume
of trade between the two sides of the Taiwan Straits this year
remained at the same level as last year, wang said.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, he said, the development of cross-the-straits
trade cannot be stopped because it is in the interests of people on
both sides of the Straits.
</P>
<P>
In looking forward to the trade development in 1997, wang
said that if the Taiwan authorities continue to pursue a policy of
tight-controls, circumstances will not be good for trade contacts,
something that we do not want to see.
</P>
<P>
But the official expressed the belief that the return of Hong
Kong to China and the possible entry of China into the World Trade
Organization will provide good opportunities for developing
economic and trade exchanges between the two sides of the
Straits.  
</P>
</TEXT>
