<HEADLINE> Iranian FM: Iran Ready to Defend Itself </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Ali
Akbar Velayati said today "Iran is ready to defend itself"
against any aggression by all means at its disposal.
</P>
<P>
Velayati told reporters here that "Iran showed very strong
resistance against any foreign invasion in the past. So we are
familiar with such aggressions. We are also familiar with
atrocity."
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted European countries concern very much about
the safety of waterway in the Gulf, which handles two thirds of
total oil in the world.
</P>
<P>
Iranian President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani had already warned
that Iran would block the waterway if it is attacked.
</P>
<P>
Velayati said recently that the situation in the
Persian Gulf is rather "tense" and "unsafe" due to foreign
military presence, especially the United States.
</P>
<P>
He called the military presence of foreign powers
"unprecedented in the world" and serves as "a obstacle to
the economic development in this part of the world."
</P>
<P>
meanwhile, Velayati today once again denied any kind of
Iranian involvement in bombing the American military base in
Dhahran last June, which killed 19 American soldiers.
</P>
<P>
He said that the United States and a number of other
countries have repeatedly accused Iran of such incidents since
the victory of the Islamic Revolution.
</P>
<P>
"But eventually it was demonstrated that all those
accusations were baseless," he added.
</P>
<P>
Speaking about the deployment of missiles on three disputed
islands in the Gulf, he said, "we have already announced the
official stance of Iran on the issue."
</P>
<P>
"What as published in Cairo as the eight countries'
communique is in fact a repetition of past statements. There
will be nothing coming out of such futile statements," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministers of Egypt, Syria and six Gulf Cooperation
Council states, members of the Damascus Declaration which was
formed in 1991 following the Gulf War, denounced in a communique
Sunday Iran for occupying three Gulf islands claimed by the United
Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
They said Iran had deployed missiles on disputed Gulf islands
of Abu Musa, Greater Tunb and Lesser Tunb in "a direct threat to
the Gulf countries" and urged immediate Iranian withdrawal from the
islands.
</P>
<P>
Velayati reiterated that "Iran would undertake any measures
deemed necessary to defend its territorial integrity within the
confines of its territory, including the three Iranian islands of
Abu Musa, the Greater and Lesser Tunb."
</P>
<P>
"The measures we undertake in our country are by no means
offensive in nature or based on expansionist goals, but merely
defensive measures," he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
