<HEADLINE> Jordan Welcomes Israeli Stand on Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 30 (Xinhua) -- A Jordanian government official
has said Jordan welcomed an Israeli stand on a proposal made by
King Hussein to grant a special status in Jerusalem, Jordan Time
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The official made the remarks Sunday while commenting
on a statement made by Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy.
</P>
<P>
"Israel's willingness to consider the proposal to begin a
dialogue between representatives of the three religions (of
Islam, Christianity and Judaism) on the special status of
Jerusalem and its holy places is positive and encouraging,"
the newspaper quoted the official as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We will consider King Hussein's proposal after the
implementation of the agreement on a military redeployment from
Hebron" on the West Bank, Levy said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"King Hussein has proposed a meeting of Moslem, Christian and
Jewish leaders to discuss a special status for Jerusalem and for
its holy places." he said.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian official said that King Hussein has stressed the
necessity that the holy city be "a symbol of peace and given a
special status for Moslems, Christians and Jews, but his appeals
did not strike a chord within Israel."
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian king called in September for the formation of an
international commission on the holy sites in Jerusalem after
Israel opened a new entrance to an archeological tunnel outside
the Al Aqsa Mosque compound, which ignited a storm of protests in
the Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
The clashes between Israeli troops and Palestinian protesters
and police left 86 people dead.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian official said that during the talks with Levy in
Amman this month, King Hussein brought up the proposal again.
</P>
<P>
The United States, the main sponsor of the Middle East peace
process and Israel's closest ally, has not publicly commented on
the proposal. The British government has reportedly welcomed the
idea.
</P>
<P>
In his comments Sunday, Levy said "King Hussein is very
concerned that the Israeli-Palestinian conflict (will) not become
a religious conflict and raised the proposal again during my
latest meeting with him."
</P>
<P>
Levy emphasized that, as far as Israel was concerned, the
proposal was not aimed at turning Jerusalem into "a capital for
the three religions" and reiterated that Israel would not give up
its claim to sovereignty over the city.
</P>
<P>
The status of Jerusalem is to be discussed between Israeli and
Palestinian negotiators as part of talks on the final
status of the Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
Jordan, which has maintained its role as the guardian of
Islamic holy sites in Jerusalem, fully supports the Palestinian
demand for the return of Arab East Jerusalem as the capital of an
independent Palestinian state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961230.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungary Witnesses Unusual Climate in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Temperatures plunged to minus
29 degrees Celsius in Hungary yesterday, making it the coldest day
in a century, the Hungarian Meteorogical Observatory said today.
</P>
<P>
The freezing weather caught Hungarians off-guard as average
daily temperatures at this time of year only fall to around minus
three degrees Celsius.
</P>
<P>
But the sub-zero temperatures are only the latest in a string
of unseasonal weather to hit the country in 1996 which caused
major problems for farmers with crop planting and harvesting.
</P>
<P>
Hungary clocked up 97 days of snowfall in winter 1995 and
spring 1996, double the normal amount.
</P>
<P>
Summer weather was also unusual, with unseasonally hot weather
in early June, violent storms in July which caused extensive
property damage, and lower than average temperatures in August.
</P>
<P>
In September, torrential rain fell across the country, three to
four times more than the seasonal average rainfall this century.
</P>
</TEXT>
