<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Economy Estimated To Grow 9.7 Percent This Year (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese economy is
estimated to grow 9.7 percent in comparable prices this year, with
a gross domestic product of 6,780 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural sector is to grow 5.1 percent while the
industrial and tertiary sectors will grow 12.3 percent and eight
percent respectively this year, announced Ye Zhen, spokesman for
the State Statistics Bureau today.
</P>
<P>
He said that China is expected to reap in more than 480 million
tons of grain this year, setting a new historical record.
</P>
<P>
Output of China's cotton crops will shrink to about four
million tons, a decrease of 800,000 tons from last
year. Meanwhile, the total amount of oil-bearing crops will go
down by 600,000 tons, reaching 21.9 million tons this year.
</P>
<P>
The decrease of cotton and oil-bearing crops is due to the
reduction of growing areas, he explained.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that China's animal husbandry and fishery
also witnessed stable growth this year, with output of both meat
and aquatic products increasing by about ten percent.
</P>
<P>
Ye said that the incremental value of Chinese industry is
expected to grow about 13 percent this year, and that the growth
rate is one percentage point less than last year.
</P>
<P>
"Production of radios, watches, bicycles, kitchen air
ventilation systems, vacuum cleaners and most textile products
dropped this year," he said, "while outputs of computers,
program-controlled switchboards, VCRs, Hi-fi systems and air
conditioners enjoyed stable growth."
</P>
<P>
He said that China's fixed assets investment is estimated to
rise 18.9 percent -- 12.5 percent in real terms with inflation
factor taken into account -- to 2,380 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that although China terminated the linking
of interest rates with price indexes and cut down the interest
rates twice this year, the market remained stable.
</P>
<P>
"This year, China's retail sales volume will grow 19.4 percent
on an annual basis, or a real growth rate of 13 percent, to 2,460
billion yuan," he said. "Generally speaking, supply is slightly
bigger than demand."
</P>
<P>
He said that China's foreign trade volume is estimated to rise
by 3.3 percent to 290 billion US dollars. The export will grow by
around three percent to 153 billion US dollars, while the import
will grow by around four percent to 137 billion US dollars. China
enjoyed a foreign trade surplus of 16 billion US dollars in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961230.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Economy Estimated To Grow 9.7 Percent This Year (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The spokesman said that China is expected to receive around 48
billion US dollars of foreign investment, with foreign direct
investment surpassing 40 billion US dollars at an increase of
seven percent over last year.
</P>
<P>
China's foreign exchange reserve reached a new level to exceed
100 billion US dollars in 1996, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
According to preliminary estimates, he said, China's retail
price index will rise by six percent this year -- a growth rate
that is about 8.8 percentage points less than that of last year.
</P>
<P>
"China has more than completed its target in macro-economic
regulation of curbing inflation at around ten percent for the
whole year and the inflation rate is much lower than the economic
growth rate," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Chinese urban people's per capita income is to
rise by 3.4 percent in real terms to 4,380 yuan this year.
</P>
<P>
As for the rural residents, he said, thanks to the raising of
grain purchase prices and a better harvest this year, their per
capita income will grow by eight percent in comparable prices to
1,900 yuan.
</P>
<P>
"To sum up, the year 1996 ushered in a stable and appropriately
growing economy for China," he said. "However, with a weak
agricultural base and the serious losses of some state-owned
enterprises, China is still confronted with a huge task in
macro-economic control, reform and development."
</P>
<P>
Looking towards 1997, Ye expressed optimism about the economic
situation.
</P>
<P>
"1997 is an extraordinarily unusual year in China's history,
with resumption of sovereignty over Hong Kong and the opening of
the 15th national congress of the Communist Party of China on the
agenda," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Judging from various factors both in the domestic and
international spheres, the Chinese economy will continue to
develop at a stable and rapid growth rate."  
</P>
</TEXT>
