<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Confidence In 1997 Handover Rising in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Prospects of Hong Kong under
China's sovereignty are becoming more and more encouraging as
1997 sets in, overshadowing the gloomy perceptions that a
confidence crisis would drag Hong Kong into demise.
</P>
<P>
The common myths to show a loss of confidence in 1997 included
huge outflows of capital, an exodus of talents, faltering economy
and political uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
However, from a review of the recent developments in Hong Kong
one can find a completely different picture and much rosy one at
that.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has enjoyed a 12-percent growth in bank deposits
since 1990, with HK dollar deposits rising steadily to account for
 55 percent of the total currency deposits now. There are no signs
 of people's confidence in the HK dollar eroding. The local
currency, pegged to the U.S. dollar, is expected to remain firm
after 1997. Moreover, the hefty foreign exchange reserves,
totaling 60 billion U.S. dollars, form the bedrock of Hong Kong's
financial stability.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is the sixth largest recipient of foreign direct
investment (FDI) among Asian developing economies, drawing 2.1
billion U.S. dollars in 1995, according to the United Nations
Conference on Trade and Development. It is also the single largest
exporter of FDI in the developing world, pumping outflows of 25
billion U.S. dollars in 1995, with a good part going to the
Chinese mainland.
</P>
<P>
Fewer people are leaving Hong Kong and more are coming in
search of opportunities. There are a great number of "returned
emigrants", who have realized that the city is still a much better
place to make a living than any of the emigrant destinations --
a clear sign of confidence in the future. With a lot of
professionals among the returnees, the anticipated brain drain is
unlikely to happen in 1997 and beyond.
</P>
<P>
Opportunity is also luring foreign companies to base their
regional headquarters in Hong Kong, a springboard into the Chinese
mainland and other Asian economies. A recent survey conducted by
the 2,700-member American Chamber of Commerce (Amcham) shows that
business confidence in Hong Kong reached a record high. Over 95
percent of the respondents are "favorable" or "very favorable" of
Hong Kong's business environment in the next five years, up four
percentage points from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Amcham Chairman Mark Michelson said: "The well-established
legal system, superior infrastructure, communications network,
free-port status and low taxes make Hong Kong a very attractive
location for regional business operations."
</P>
<P>
As a main barometer of Hong Kong's economy, property market
bottomed out in January and gained strong momentum throughout the
year. Property developers paid record high prices to bid for lots
of land at auction, banks competed to cut mortgage loan rates to
lure home buyers, and rentals and purchases prices for houses and
office buildings jumped. The latest government statistics show
that agreements for sales and purchases of properties in November
shot up 100 percent in volume, and 300 percent in value over the
same month of 1995. Buying properties is really a test of
confidence in the future of the city, said a securities
researcher.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
