<DOCNO> XIE19961230.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Displaced Workers in China Seek New Opportunities (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- It's been more than six months
since Zhang Xinlan was displaced from her job in a machine
fittings factory in Beijing. After an initial period of deep
frustration, she has finally come to terms with her situation.
</P>
<P>
"This was a crisis that had to be overcome sooner or later,"
the 28-year-old woman said. "The important thing is to find
another job."
</P>
<P>
Due to management difficulties, the factory where Zhang worked
was forced to suspend part of its production last April, and more
than 40 employees including Zhang were displaced -- virtually laid
off.
</P>
<P>
Zhang's case is not rare in today's China, which is in the
process of a far-reaching marketization drive. Since the late
1980s, the number of displaced workers has been on the rise,
reaching some seven million by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Officially speaking, displacement, or "xiagang" in Chinese, is
similar to, yet different from unemployment. A displaced worker no
longer has a job, but if conditions improve in the factory and the
worker is needed again, his former post becomes available again.
</P>
<P>
In reality, this doesn't often happen. In China, the vast
majority of state-owned enterprises suffer from the problems of
low efficiency and too many workers doing the same job. A reduced
staff and enhanced efficiency are crucial in order to establish a
management mechanism in line with a market economy.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, displacement, like unemployment, spells troubles.
</P>
<P>
"With state-owned enterprises deepening their reform and the
country readjusting its industrial structure, China is bound to
have more displaced workers and thus be under increased pressure
from unemployment," said Bai Hejin, deputy secretary-general of the
State Planning Commission. "And the state is seeking solutions for
the problem."
</P>
<P>
Despite the rising displacement, China still maintains a good
employment record. By the end of this year, the registered number
of jobless people in cities and towns has reached 5.6 million,
representing an unemployment rate of three percent.
</P>
<P>
Lu Jianhua, a sociologist with the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences, said that displacement is a "sensible and realistic
transitional measure" by the state, taking into account both the
reform and social stability.
</P>
<P>
Under the former planned economic system, he pointed out, the
welfare of Chinese workers was the duty of employers due to the
lack a well-developed social security system.
</P>
<P>
Qiao Jian, a specialist on labor relations and the host of a
workers' hotline in the Chinese capital, has taken notice of the
shift of the displaced workers' focus of attention in recent years.
</P>
<P>
"In the past, most of the phone calls were bitter complaints,
and the callers were apparently deeply depressed," said Qiao. "Now
the callers have become much calmer, and are mostly interested in
how to find a new job."
</P>
<P>
He added that Chinese workers, accustomed to the idea of
lifelong employment in state-owned enterprises -- a practice known
in China as the "iron rice bowl" -- have gradually accepted a new
understanding of employment under the market economy, and their
ability to withstand the pressure of job displacement has been
enhanced.
</P>
<P>
The result of a survey on displaced women workers in Shanghai,
China's most economically developed city, supports Qiao's
assumption. Only three percent of those surveyed said they thought
it is "a shame to go out all by oneself to look for a new job."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
