<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Deposits, Loans Rise in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's deposits, loans
and advances rose in November, according to statistics from the
Hong Kong Monetary Authority.
</P>
<P>
Total deposits rose by 3.6 percent in November, following a
growth of 1.7 percent in October. The increase was mainly led by
a 5.2 percent growth in HK dollar deposits, which outpaced a 1.5
percent rise in foreign currency deposits.
</P>
<P>
HK dollar deposits recorded notable growth in both time
deposits and savings deposits.
</P>
<P>
Savings and time deposits rose by 4.1 and 6.6 percent
respectively, compared to their respective growth of 2.3 percent
and 3.5 percent in the previous month.
</P>
<P>
Total loans and advances grew by 2.5 percent in November,
following a slight rise of 0.1 percent in October. The rise was
broadly based, with an expansion in domestic credit by 4 percent
and a rise in offshore loans by 1.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Of the domestic credit, loans for trade financing rose by 0.4
percent in November, the first monthly increase after consecutive
declines in the previous four months.  
</P>
</TEXT>
