<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Confidence In 1997 Handover Rising In HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
For Hong Kong's economy in 1997, optimism prevails, with GDP
growth forecast at above five percent along with robust consumer
spending and export volume. This year, retail market has staged a
modest but sustainable recovery and the unemployment rate has
fallen to 2.7 percent from 3.5 percent a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Optimism is also creeping into many opinion polls that track
Hong Kong people's sentiment toward the handover. A recent social
survey conducted by the University of Hong Kong shows that 70
percent of people are confident in Hong Kong's future overall. It
is the highest level ever recorded since the university began
tracking confidence in January 1994.
</P>
<P>
The selection of the administrative leader and of the
provisional legislature this month fortified Hong Kong people's
confidence in the future Special Administrative Region (SAR).
These two political events, broadcast live on the local radio and
television, convinced Hong Kong people of Beijing's determination
to fully implement the principles of "one country, two systems",
"Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong" and a high degree of
autonomy.
</P>
<P>
Upbeat sentiments prevail in the community when transition is
going into the substantial stage and preparations for forming the
HKSAR government are in full swing. Tung Chee Hwa, HKSAR Chief
Executive designate, is widely accepted as a leader of
credibility, who wrapped up an overwhelming majority of 320 votes
from a 400-strong Selection Committee on December 11. Brushing
aside previous misunderstandings, many local citizens are
supportive to the 60-seat Provisional Legislative Council (PLC),
which, elected on December 21, is essential to avoid a "legal
vacuum" after Hong Kong's handover in mid-1997.
</P>
<P>
As Tung Chee Hwa put it, the only resource Hong Kong has is its
wealthy human talents, who are sufficiently equipped to face
challenges. Over the past 150 years, Hong Kong people have time
and again turned uncertainties into opportunities for big
development with resilience, dynamism and entrepreneur spirit.
That is why more and more Hong Kong people have come to believe
that 1997 is a process, not a date.  
</P>
</TEXT>
