<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria To Benefit From WHO's Anti-Cholera </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria and 15 other West
African countries are to benefit from an anti-cholera project
sponsored by the World Health Organization (WHO), the "Guardian"
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a WHO report as saying that the annual cases
of cholera in west Africa has exploded from 7,000 in 1993 to
42,500 in the first nine months of this year, a more than
six-fold increase.
</P>
<P>
The number of cholera fatalities has risen even faster during
the same period from 369 deaths in 1993 to more than 2,900 this
year, the WHO report said.
</P>
<P>
West Africa now accounts for two-thirds of the cases on the
continent and more than 70 percent of all cholera deaths, said
the report.
</P>
<P>
The anti-cholera project will be jointly funded by the
Regional Office for Africa of the WHo and a special grant from
the Swiss government.
</P>
<P>
The project aims to reduce the cholera fatality to one percent
or less by improving case management, especially by promoting
greater use of the oral rehydration solution and in severe cases,
appropriate antibiotics, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Other beneficiary countries are Benin, Burkina Faso, Cameroon,
Chad, Cote d'Ivoire, Gambia, Ghana, Guinea, Guinea-Bissau,
Liberia, Mali, Niger, Senegal, Sierra Leone and Togo, the report
added.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Nigeria has been ranked among the
worst 16 countries in the world in terms of last year's
Under-Five-Child Mortality Rate by the just-released State of the
World Children, 1997, a publication of the United Nations
Children Fund UNICEF).
</P>
<P>
According to the UNICEF report, Nigeria has an under-five
child mortality rate of 191 per 1,000, showing no big difference
with the rate of 204 per 1,000 at its independence in 1960.
</P>
</TEXT>
