<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Displaced Workers in China Seek New Opportunities (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Xu Zhenghui, the labor division chief with the All-China
Federation of Trade Unions, said displacement is closely related
to workers' immediate interests, and it is unavoidable that some
workers have reacted in a drastic way.
</P>
<P>
Displacement, though a potential destabilizing factor, has not
had much impact on social stability, Xu pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"The good thing is that the whole society is showing concern
for displaced workers, and governments from the central level down
to the local levels and social organizations are working together
to find ways out for these workers," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government launched a re-employment project last
year, aimed at helping displaced and laid off people to find new
jobs.
</P>
<P>
The project, by way of fund appropriation and policy guidance,
incorporated promotion of the service industry, small enterprises
and community services, and increased services in employment
information, unemployment insurance and training for
reassignment. It is being carried out in 200 cities in 22
provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities.
</P>
<P>
In Shanghai, a re-employment service center has been set up,
which provides training for displaced workers and helps them
either find jobs in other facilities or start their own business.
</P>
<P>
Some 860,000 people have been laid off in the city over the
past five years; 660,000 of them have found new positions.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Xinlan is interested in dressmaking, and has been
attending a dressmaker's training course for four months. "I'd
like to try my hand at opening a little dressmaking shop," she
said.
</P>
<P>
And many who were displaced before Zhang have started new
businesses. Wang Ruizhen, a former textile worker in the east
China city of Qingdao, opened a furniture store in the latter half
of last year, with the support of the local government. The
38-year-old woman has since accumulated assets worth several
hundreds of thousands of yuan.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, three million people have
turned to professional counseling services, 1.1 million attended
reassignment training courses, and 2.43 million landed new jobs
under the re-employment project.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Labor said China will continue to organize 2.5
million displaced and laid off workers to participate in the
project.
</P>
<P>
Some displaced workers still face problems of difficult living
conditions, admitted Bai Hejin of the State Planning
Commission. He said the state grants temporary subsidies to those
who have a hard time keeping minimum standards of living. Two
million people across the country have received the subsidies.
</P>
<P>
"For long-term benefits," Bai noted, "the government will
create more job opportunities by furthering economic expansion. On
the other hand, it will accelerate the reform process and strive
to build a complete social security system that covers workers
of all kinds of enterprises by the end of the century."
</P>
<P>
A sample survey made recently by the State Commission for
Restructuring the Economy shows that the vast majority of workers
support the ongoing reform of the economic system, and agree over
the direction the reform is taking.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
