<HEADLINE> Great Successes in Sino-African Relations in 1996: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Great achievements have been
scored in Sino-African relations in 1996 thanks to joint efforts
from the two sides, Chinese Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister Qian
Qichen said today.
</P>
<P>
Qian said in an interview with Xinhua that there have been
frequent high-level exchange of visits between China and African
countries this year.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin visited six African countries this
May and spelled out a five-point proposal on Sino-African
relations, forging a solid basis that will allow for a long-term,
stable, and comprehensive cooperative relationship between China
and African countries and enable them to successfully usher in the
21st century, Qian said.
</P>
<P>
China pays close attention to Africa, the foreign minister
said, adding that non-colonization on the African continent is one
of the significant achievements of human civilization after World
War II, Qian said.
</P>
<P>
Most African countries stick to the "one China" policy, and the
"pragmatic diplomacy" carried out by Taiwan has become
increasingly unpopular, Qian noted.
</P>
<P>
China and African countries have further increased their
consultation and cooperation in international affairs, he said. In
the recent election for U.N. Secretary-General, China and African
countries agreed that the U.N. chief official should be elected
from a candidate proposed by African countries.
</P>
<P>
Qian said he believed that China and African countries will
create a brighter future in Sino-African relations.
</P>
</TEXT>
