<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Law on Stationing Troops in HK SAR Adopted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The Law on Stationing Troops
in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) was adopted
at the 23rd session of the Standing Committee of the Eighth
National People's Congress in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
New revisions were made on two articles of the draft law, based
on the revisions made at the last session of the NPC Standing
Committee.
</P>
<P>
After the rewrite, the fourth clause of Article 16 of the law
states that the military personnel "shall take good care of the
public property of the Hong Kong SAR and the private property
owned by the Hong Kong residents as well as other people."
</P>
<P>
The previous version said that the military personnel "shall
take good care of the public property of the Hong Kong SAR and the
private property owned by the Hong Kong residents."
</P>
<P>
As some members suggested that stricter stipulations be made on
the issue that the troops and military personnel shall not be
engaged in the profit-making businesses, Article 18 was revised as
follows: "The troops and military personnel stationed in the Hong
Kong SAR shall not be engaged in profit-making businesses by any
forms, nor can the military personnel be engaged in any other
activity incompatible with their obligation."
</P>
<P>
The Law on Stationing Troops in the Hong Kong SAR contains 30
articles in six chapters, including the general principles, the
obligations of the troops, the relationship between the troops and
the Hong Kong SAR government, duties and discipline of the
military personnel, jurisdiction concerned with the military
personnel, and supplementary provisions.
</P>
<P>
The law will go into effect on July 1, 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
