<HEADLINE> Israelis, Palestinians to Continue Hebron Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators are scheduled to hold another round of talks this
afternoon on the Israeli army's redeployment in the West Bank
town of Hebron, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, Israeli army Chief
of Staff Amnon Lipkin-Shahak and Palestinian top negotiator
Mahmoud Abbas will join in the talks on a later stage.
</P>
<P>
A decision will be taken in the evening for setting up a
timetable for another summit meeting between Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu and Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
President Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
After a 90-minute meeting with Arafat Sunday night in Gaza,
Mordechai expressed his hope that the outstanding differences
could be resolved during today's negotiations.
</P>
<P>
However, Arafat said that an agreement has not been reached
on the question of joint patrol close to the Machpela Cave (the
Ibrahimi Mosque), and on the Palestinian demand that a
prisoners-release coincide with the redeployment.
</P>
<P>
A Palestinian source told Israel Radio that progress was made
at Sunday night's talks, and he predicted that a
Netanyahu-Arafat summit would take place Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.S. special Middle East coordinator Dennis Ross is
due to arrive today in a bid to bring the final stages of
the protracted Hebron talks to a successful conclusion.
</P>
<P>
Today's Jerusalem Post quoted an unidentified U.S. official as
saying that Washington is heartened by what they call Egypt's
"support for the Palestinians (in) wrapping up the talks."
</P>
<P>
Arafat returned from the Egyptian capital of Cairo last night
after talks with President Hosni Mubarak on the latest
development of the Israeli-Palestinian negotiations on Hebron.
</P>
