<HEADLINE> S. Korea Returns Remains of Armed DPRK People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 30 (Xinhua) -- South Korea today returned the
remains of the 24 armed people of the Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK) killed or found dead in the submarine incident
last September.
</P>
<P>
The repatriation was conducted at the DPRK's request at the
truce village of Panmunjon this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Seoul agreed to return the remains of the DPRK people after
Pyongyang expressed deep regret on Sunday for the submarine
incident and promised to make efforts to ensure that such an
incident will not recur.
</P>
<P>
South Korea said that a total of 26 armed DPRK people
"infiltrated into" the country's Kangwon Province from a grounded
submarine in the East Sea (Sea of Japan) on September 18 this year.
</P>
<P>
Of the 26 DPRK people, one is still at large, while 13 were
shot dead by South Korean troops, 11 were found killed by their
colleagues and one was captured alive in a massive manhut in the
rugged mountains.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK said that the submarine, while on a training mission,
drifted after having an engine trouble and hitting a rock in the
sea.
</P>
<P>
However, Seoul claimed that the case of the intrusion was not
an "inadvertent incident that occurred during routine training" as
Pyongyang said, but was a "carefully premediated act of
Provocation." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
