<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-30 10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Parliament Sets Deficit Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The Finance Committee of
the Knesset (Israel's parliament) has approved a bill which will
set definite limits for the deficit in each of the next five
years, today's Jerusalem Post reported.
</P>
<P>
The bill, which is meant to give investors the message that
the Israeli government is serious about deficit reduction, now
will be sent back to the Knesset plenum for its second and third
readings.
</P>
<P>
However, it will have no real binding force even if passed,
since it can always be amended. This is what the previous
government did in 1994, when it saw it would not be able to meet
the targets specified in an earlier law.
</P>
<P>
According to the bill, the 1997 deficit will have to be no
greater than 2.8 percent of the gross domestic product (GDP),
and the limit will then decrease to 2.4 percent in 1998,
2 percent in 1999, 1.75 percent in 2000 and 1.5 percent in 2001.
</P>
<P>
These targets are considerably less ambitious than those
included in the original Deficit Reduction Law, passed by the
previous Likud government in 1992, which stipulated the deficit of
6.2 percent in 1992, 3.2 percent in 1993, 2.2 percent in 1994
and zero in 1995.
</P>
<P>
However, the report said it is more stringent than the
amended version passed by the previous Labor government in 1994,
since it sets specific targets for the deficit.
</P>
<P>
The Labor bill stated that the deficit would be 3 percent in
1994 and would decrease by unspecified amounts in each of the
three following years, but, the deficit hit 3.2 percent in 1995
and is expected to be some 3.8 percent this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
