<DOCNO> XIE19961230.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea's Current Account Deficit to Surpass $23 B </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 30 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's current account
deficit is expected to exceed 23 billion U.S. dollars this year,
the Bank of Korea said here today.
</P>
<P>
The country's current account deficit in November was 1.87
billion U.S. dollars, bringing the cumulative total for the first
11 months of this year to 21.64 billion U.S. dollars, more than
twice the red-ink figure of 8.6 billion U.S. dollars recorded for
the same period last year, the central bank said.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that lackluster exports due to labor strikes in
December will push up the current account deficit for the entire
year beyond the 23-billion-U.S.-dollar level.
</P>
<P>
The ever-growing current account deficit, accounting for 4
percent of the gross national product (GNP) in excess of the
country's sustainable level of 2 to 3 percent, may result in such
side effects as increased foreign debt and unemployment, a bank
official said.
</P>
<P>
The official attributed the spiraling current account deficit
mainly to the poor performance of exports.
</P>
<P>
During the first 11 months of this year, South Korea's exports
totaled 117.97 billion U.S. dollars, while imports amounted to
136.61 billion U.S. dollars, for a deficit of 18.64 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the country's trade deficit stood at 10.06 billion
U.S. dollars, up 58.7 percent from the 6.34 billion U.S. dollars
registered in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
