<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Investment Speeds Up Economic Development in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Rapid economic growth in
China's economic powerhouse of Shanghai this year has been
attributed partly to overseas investment being raised rationally
and used with high-efficiency.
</P>
<P>
This year the city witnessed a rare higher economic growth, but
with the lowerest inflation rate since the founding of New
China in 1949, with the economic growth rate reaching 12.9 percent,
and per-capita GDP reaching nearly 2,700 US dollars during the
January-November period.
</P>
<P>
The first 11 months this year saw the city's retail sales top
100 billion yuan, with retail prices dropping nearly eight
percentage points compared with the same period in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The city has applied the bulk of overseas investments to local
industrial, urban construction, agricultural projects as well as
service trades, helping greatly improve the local restructuring of
the industrial structure.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 percent of local overseas-financed projects are
involved in large-scale and hi-tech industrial fields, such as
automobiles, electronics, computers, biological pharmaceuticals
and fine chemicals.
</P>
<P>
The city has given priority to hi-tech,
lower-energy-consumption projects, as well as projects with a high
added value, instead of the former labor-intensive and
high-energy-consumption sectors, with the output value of hi-tech
projects accounting for 12 percent of the local industrial total,
up from two percent of ten years ago.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the six leading industries, involving automobiles,
iron and steel, telecommunications, petrochemicals, household
appliances and power station equipment, have kept a growing
momentum, and generated half of the local total industrial output
value, helping the city form five industrial production bases in
Baoshan District, Jiading County, the Pudong New Area, the Minhang
Economic Development Zone and Jinshan Area.
</P>
<P>
The utilization of overseas investment has also given an
impetus to the development of local service trades, building
finance, insurance, real estate, telecommunications,
transportation, tourism to become new economic growth forces.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1990's, more than 190 overseas-funded financial
organizations and representative offices have been set up in
Shanghai, enabling the financial sector to grow at an annual rate
of 12.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Foreign trade is expected to rise more than 10 percent this
year over 1996. Foreign-funded enterprises will contribute 87
percent to increased exports this year.
</P>
<P>
The inflow of overseas funds into urban construction has
given a greater boost to the improvement of the local investment
environment, helping to build the city into an international
commercial, financial and trade center in the near future.
</P>
<P>
During recent years, the city has undertaken 18,000
foreign-funded projects, with contracted overseas investment
surpassing 50 billion US dollars, greatly speeding up local
economic development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
