<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Angola's Peace Process Goes in Depth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Yin Yongjian)
</P>
<P>
LUANDA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The warring parties in Angola
has made great achievements in procuring peace in the war-plagued
country in 19
 090he second year for the implementation of the
Lusaka Peace Accord.
</P>
<P>
The achievements are manifested mainly in the assembly of the
militiamen of the former rebel National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA), the handover of their weapons and
the formation of a new unified army.
</P>
<P>
UNITA began to assemble its men on November 20, 1995, the
first anniversary of the signing of the Lusaka Peace Accord. By
November 26 this year, UNITA soldiers assembled in 15 assembly
points set up acro ndependence of Angola (UNITA), the handover of their weapons and
the formation of a new unified army.
</P>
<P>
UNITA began to assemble its men on November 20, 1995, the
first anniversary of the signing of the Lusaka Peace Accord. By
November 26 this year, UNITA soldiers assembled in 15 assembly
points set up acro ndependence of Angola (UNITA), the handover of their weapons and
the formation of a new unified army.
</P>
<P>
UNITA began to assemble its men on November 20, 1995, the
first anniversary of the signin52,000 tons of ammunition, of which 1,500 tons
have been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, over 660 UNITA soldiers under the age of 18 have
been civilianized.
</P>
<P>
More than 18,080 former UNITA rebels have been enroled in the
unified Angolan army. Nine UNITA generals have arrived in the
capital of Luanda to take the posts of deputy defense minister,
deputy chief of the general staff of the armed forces and deputy
chief of staff of the army respectively.
</P>
<P>
Besides, a total of 539 war prisoners have been released by
the two warring factions, of which 369 are former UNITA rebels.
</P>
<P>
The military obstacles to the peace in Angola have been
removed on the whole and the peace process in the southern
African country will soon enter into the political stage, said
Blondin Beye, the United Nations Special Envoy in Angola, at a
meeting of the Angola Peace Joint Commission on November 21.
</P>
<P>
During the "political stage", the following political
issues will be solved -- the position of UNITA leader Jonas
Savimbi in the government, the establishment of local
governments, UNITA's admission into the parliament, and the
formation of a new government of national unity.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that the solution of these political
issues is as difficult as that of the military ones, and
Savimbi's position in the new government will be a thorny one.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government once came up with a proposal that the
UNITA chief be appointed the second vice-president of Angola, but
UNITA rejected it. UNITA proposed that Savimbi be appointed
Angola's opposition leader, which was rejected by the government.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations are being held between the two sides on this
critical issue, which, observers believe, might have influence on
the peace process in Angola.
</P>
<P>
Although there are many difficulties on the way forward, the
prospects of peace process in Angola are rosy, observers say.
</P>
<P>
Both Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos and UNITA
leader Jonas Savimbi have expressed their will to solve the
problems of Angola by political means, instead of by war.
</P>
<P>
They believe that most of the outstanding issues will be
resolved before UNAVEM concludes its mission in February next
year. Peace process in Angola seems irrevocable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
