<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Phone Company Asks for Action Against U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 30 (Xinhua) -- India's Videsh Sanchar Nigam
ltd (VSNL), the state-owned local telephone monopoly service
provider for international calls, has demanded action against the
U.S.-based carriers like MCI and Sprint for promoting call-call
traffic from India, official sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
The VSNL and the U.S. telecom regulator Federation
Communications Commission (FCC) have had the bitter war of words
over the latter's call-back issue in the past. The VSNL has fired
off a missive to the Department of Telecommunications (DOT) in the
country demanding that strict measures should be taken if the U.S.
carriers do not stop abetting call-back traffic, estimated to be
as high as 100 million minutes of traffic of both incoming and
outgoing as against a total of 1.2 billion minutes that India
handles.
</P>
<P>
The VSNL's move is the latest rapier thrust in the battle with
the U.S. regulator that began with the FCC's controversial bid to
force a cutback in telecom rates the world over. In the letter to
the DOT, VSNL Chairman and managing director B.K. Syngal has asked
the department to inform the FCC that call-back services are
illegal in India. The VSNL has also urged the department to come
out with advertisements in the media declaring call-back services
illegal. Call-back services have been declared legal by the FCC.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the U.S. regulator had not accepted a letter from VSNL
on the issue since it does not recognize the Indian International
Telecom Services Provider as an official counterpart.
</P>
<P>
The call-back service is an option that enables local telephone
subscribers to take advantage of the low rates in countries like
the U.S. while putting through international calls.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
