<HEADLINE> Nepali Opposition Seeks Alternative to Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's main opposition is
working to avert possible fresh parliamentary elections by seeking
an alternative to the present three-party coalition government,
local newspapers said today.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxist
Leninist, CPN-UML) are trying to work out an alternative to the
government, led by Sher Bahadur Deuba of the Nepali Congress (NC),
from fears that the government would call for mid-term elections
if it fails to win back majority support in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The Deuba government only won minority support in the lower
house last week when a CPN-UML tabled no-trust motion was put to
the vote.
</P>
<P>
However, the motion was rejected by the 205-seat house as 101
MPs voted for and 84 MPs against it. It required a majority of 103
votes to pass under the Constitution of Nepal.
</P>
<P>
After his government survived the opposition challenge, Deuba
vowed that he would neither resign nor call for mid-term
elections.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said the government would seek a vote of
confidence in the next parliament session probably in February
1997.
</P>
<P>
A Supreme Court's verdict last year ruled out the possibility
of fresh elections if there is a possibility of an alternative
government in the house, the newspapers said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a four-day Central Committee meeting of the main
opposition party concluding here Sunday decided to stage a
one-month street demonstration program against the government in
14 major cities throughout the country next month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
