<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 29 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
on Sunday welcomed an apology from the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea for a submarine incident, which occurred three
months ago.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK on Sunday expressed "deep regret" for the submarine
which ran aground off the South Korean coast in September, and
said it will "make efforts to ensure that such an incident will
not recur and will work with others for durable peace and
stability on the Korean Peninsula."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he was "pleased" with DPRK's promise to avoid such
kind of incidents in the future.
</P>
<P>
"I am pleased that Pyongyang has pledged to prevent the
recurrence of such an incident and has expressed its willingness
to work with others for durable peace and stability on the
peninsula," he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The United States, on behalf of South Korea that demanded an
apology before improving relations with DPRK, has been negotiating
on the submarine issue with DPRK's envoys in New York ever since
the submarine incident took place.
</P>
<P>
Clinton hoped the DPRK's statement would possibly open the way
toward four-party talks on Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
"I hope discussions can now begin to move forward on the
four-party peace talks," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Secretary of State Warren Christopher said
the United States would consider food aid to the DPRK if it
apologized, but there was no immediate word on that in Clinton's
statement. 
