<HEADLINE> Qian Qichen on Sino-Japanese Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Aside from one major
roadblock, Sino-Japanese relations have generally maintained their
prescribed course of development since the beginning of this year,
Chinese Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen said here
today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, Qian said that bilateral
cooperation and exchanges in every area have been furthered, and
that bilateral trade volume is expected to be above 60 billion US
dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted, the normal development of bilateral ties has
been hindered due to Japan's wrong attitude towards its history of
aggression against China and its wrong position on Diaoyu Island.
</P>
<P>
The appropriate recognition and treatment of past acts against
China by the Japanese militarists has a strong bearing on the
political foundation of China-Japan ties, Qian said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the Chinese side has always held that the
friendship between the peoples of the two countries should be
enhanced from generation to generation.
</P>
<P>
However, the Chinese foreign minister noted, it is necessary
for the Japanese to recognize and acknowledge that period of
history.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that not long ago, leaders of both countries held
important talks in Manila, and that China then hoped the Japanese
side would translate its commitment into action, in order to push
forward the sound, stable and sustained development of bilateral
relations.  
</P>
