<HEADLINE> Swedish People Take Passive Attitude to EMU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Swedish people took a
passive attitude of joining the European Monetary Union (EMU),
according to a latest poll conducted by local newspaper Dagens
Nyheter (Daily News).
</P>
<P>
Forty-four percent of the 1,000 people in the poll published
today opposed Sweden's participation in the union while one-third
supported and another one-third still undecided.
</P>
<P>
More Swedish people took the passive attitude to the
participation than that in the October survey, in which 38 percent
of people opposed.
</P>
<P>
Swedish Prime Minister Goran Persson said, in an article
carried today in the daily Svenska Dagbladet (Sweden Daily), that
debates on the issue should be held in the country. He was
concerned that if Sweden joins the union, it has to carry out
super national policy on taxes and other charges, which is against
Swedish people's wish.
</P>
<P>
Sweden has not yet decided to join the union among the first
countries in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961230.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Illegal Immigrants in Thailand Found to Carry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Syphilis, elephantiasis and
tuberculosis are three major diseases carried into Thailand by
illegal immigrants, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Health examinations conducted on more than 160,000 immigrant
workers registered at the Thai Labor and Social Welfare Ministry
in September-November 1996 showed a high rate of syphilis, a
sexually transmitted disease which indicates a risk of HIV/AIDS
infection, said Permanent Secretary of the Public Health Ministry
Vitura Sangsingkeo.
</P>
<P>
The health report, based on information from some 400 hospitals
in the country's 43 provinces declared as amnesty zones for
illegal workers, showed 843 cases of syphilis among the
immigrants, 514 of tuberculosis, 357 of elephantiasis, 58 of
malaria and two of leprosy.
</P>
<P>
Vitura said the Public Health Ministry is particularly worried
about the spread of elephantiasis and malaria in the country.
</P>
<P>
Although Thailand successfully controlled the spread of
elephantiasis several years ago, it could return as a major
communicable disease as it is carried by mosquitoes, Vitura said.
</P>
<P>
Malaria, which mainly infects people living in Thai provinces
neighboring Myanmar and Cambodia, is known for its resistance to
drugs, said Vitura.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961230.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Riot Town Returns to Normal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JARKARTA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The situation in Tasikmalaya
in West Java Province of Indonesia has returned to normal after a
mass riot last Thursday that killed at least four residents and
injured 15 others, the local press today quoted police as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Police and military officers continue to be on alert," a
police officer of the Tasikmalaya police district said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
By Sunday afternoon, police had detained 93 suspects for
allegedly engaging in destruction and burning, said the police.
</P>
<P>
"We are still probing the case to find out possible
masterminds," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Market and public transportation started operating since
Saturday as residents, students, youths and military officers
worked together to clean up the burned site, the police said.
</P>
<P>
The local government estimated the losses at more than 50
billion rupiah (about 21.8 million U.S. dollars) from the more
than 100 seriously damaged and burned buildings including
factories, churches, stores, banks, police stations, automobile
showrooms, vehicles and schools.
</P>
<P>
The local manpower office disclosed that at least 1,000 workers
would possibly be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
The riot started as a protest by thousands of Muslims against
alleged police mistreatment of three Muslim teachers in the town,
about 225 kilometers southeast of Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
Religious Affairs Minister Tarmizi Taher expressed his regret
over the incident, calling it a social brutality containing
religious elements.
</P>
<P>
"It was not a religious conflict at first but a political and
power abuse," he said.
</P>
<P>
Quoting reports from the ministry's fact finding team, Taher
indicated that certain groups of people have made use of the
incident.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
