<HEADLINE> 1996 Sees China's Active Multi-faceted Diplomacy: Foreign Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Beijing, December 30 (Xinhua) -- China's active, multi-faceted
and multi-level diplomacy in 1996 has enhanced the country's
relations with the rest of the world, offering a positive
contribution to worldwide peace and development, Chinese
Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen said in an interview
with Xinhua here today.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic endeavors, particularly the exchange of visits by
senior leaders, have reinforced the friendship and cooperation
between China and the developing countries, on the basis of the
Five Principles of Peaceful Co-existence, Qian pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The noticeable results of the diplomacy are partly manifested
in the positive development trend of the relations between China
and Western countries, and in the increasing, positive and
important role played by China in major international affairs,
Qian said. He cited in particular the establishment of the new
Asian-European relationship, the strengthening of economic and
technological cooperation in the Asian-Pacific region, and the
conclusion of the treaty on complete prohibition of nuclear
testing.
</P>
<P>
And the international community highly regards and appreciates
China's active involvement in global affairs, Qian added.
</P>
<P>
In its contacts with foreign countries, China has moved quickly
to forcefully counter-attack practices that infringe upon China's
sovereignty or intervene in China's internal affairs, Qian said,
thus effectively safeguarding the state sovereignty, territorial
integrity and national dignity.
</P>
<P>
The diplomatic achievements in the past year have also helped
create a more favorable international environment for the
country's modernization drive, and will help to guarantee the
stable transition of Hong Kong while promoting national
reunification, according to the vice-premier and foreign
minister.  
</P>
</TEXT>
