<HEADLINE> Conspicuous Progress in Global Multi-polarization Recorded in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The most outstanding
characteristic of the international situation in 1996 has been the
conspicuous progress of multi-polarization, both politically and
economically, and both globally and regionally.
</P>
<P>
During an interview with Xinhua here today, Chinese
Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen also said the
relations between the world's big powers are undergoing major
readjustments, marked by mutual reliance and restraint, which have
brought about a complicated and changeable situation.
</P>
<P>
The Helms-Burton Bill and the D'amato Bill, enacted by the
United States to encourage other countries to impose economic
sanctions against Cuba and Iran, have been strongly condemned and
extensively boycotted, and seemed unlikely to be implemented.
</P>
<P>
Citing other evidence to support his statement, Qian said the
Asian-European Meeting held in March in Thailand -- the first of
its kind attracting leaders of 25 countries to discuss their
future cooperation on equal footing -- reflected "a historical
change in the Asian-European relationship" and the advances in
global multi-polarization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
