<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mobile Libraries Appear on Beijing Streets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Libraries in Beijing no longer
wait for readers and they are now going to their doorsteps.
</P>
<P>
In the service, book-carriers are used. One carrier can hold
nearly 3,000 books at a time. Librarians can work on the carrier,
which is very convenient to both readers and librarians.
</P>
<P>
Since the Chaoyang District Library in east Beijing began
providing the service in 1990, over 700 thousand local residents
have never worried about reading books, newspapers and magazines.
</P>
<P>
This service, welcomed by the residents, is called "mobile
library".
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Children and Youth Library has joined in the group,
providing books on literature and arts. More than 1,000 children
become its customers.
</P>
<P>
The library also delivers books to correction centers for
juvenile delinquents.
</P>
<P>
"The mobile library has provided many good books to us, and we
have learned how to behave rightly through reading," said a
delinquent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
