<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North China Province Expecting Tourism Boom in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Visit China '97, the
national tourist campaign, will give north China's Hebei Province
an opportunity to receive more foreign visitors.
</P>
<P>
Hebei does not intend to miss out on the chance to show off
its many tourist attractions, according to Wang Xinyong, deputy
director of the Provincial Tourism Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that the province has specially selected 35
well-known tourist attractions out of more than 1,000 scenic spots
for overseas visitors, including the world's largest imperial
garden, the Summer Resort in Cheng, Beidai River, and the Shanhai
Pass.
</P>
<P>
He said that in addition, a series of celebration activities
will be held, such as the Zhuozhou Flower and Lantern Festival in
February, the Chengde International Tourism Festival in July, and
the Cangzhou Martial Arts Festival in September.
</P>
<P>
Travel agencies from more than 20 countries including
Singapore, Japan, Malaysia, and Britain have promised to attend a
large moon-appreciation event, which is scheduled for the
Mid-Autumn Day (15th day of the 8th lunar month) period at the
Zhuozhou Movie and TV Town.
</P>
<P>
Hebei earned 58 million US dollars from 240,000 overseas
tourists in the first eleven months of this year, he said, adding
that the province was visited by 25 million domestic tourists
during the same period.
</P>
<P>
Hebei is upgrading its transport conditions to cater for the
increasing number of tourists. Roads near scenic spots are being
widened and renovated. An express train service will start between
the provincial capital of Shijiazhuang and Beijing. Luxury
trains will link the area with Russia's capital of Moscow. And the
province will also open more sea routes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
