<DATE_TIME> 1996-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Coastal City Develops Marine Service Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WEIHAI, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Rongcheng, a coastal city in
east China's Shandong Province, has built the service trade into a
driving force behind local marine economic development.
</P>
<P>
With nearly 500 kilometers of coastline and 80 harbors, the
city has a favorable geographical condition to develop the service
sector including marine transportation and coastal tourism.
</P>
<P>
The city now has 21 cargo ships, with a total DWT of 36,500
tons, and it has opened eight shipping routes to Hong Kong, Macao,
and Japan.
</P>
<P>
The city's Longxu Island has taken advantage of its Longyan
harbour, an open national-level port, to invest 69 million yuan in
setting up three shipping companies, which have 14 oil tankers and
cargo ships, and opened five international shipping routes.
</P>
<P>
During the January-November period this year, the island made
50 million yuan in profits from shipping services.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the city also attaches more importance to ocean
shipping of fresh marine products, with more than 100 ships for
the transportation trade.
</P>
<P>
It has earned more than 50 million US dollars in foreign
exchange from fresh sea product shipments during the first eleven
months of this year.
</P>
<P>
In order to develop local rich tourism resources, the city has
built 200 km of coastal highways, and restored and added
several scenic spots, historical sites and entertainment zones.
</P>
<P>
The city has been visited by 650,000 domestic and overseas
tourists so far this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
