<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Serbian Parliament Speaker on OSCE Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Speaker of the Serbian
Parliament Dragan Tomic has said the report of the Organization
for Security and Cooperation in Europe on Yugoslav political
disputes was preliminary.
</P>
<P>
"The report can be an information as well as a recommendation
but the OSCE cannot arbitrate and this has been confirmed by
Felipe Gonzalez who headed an OSCE delegation for a fact-finding
mission," Tanjug news agency quoted Tomic on Sunday as saying.
</P>
<P>
The OSCE delegation came to Belgrade on December 20 for a
two-day visit at the invitation of the Yugoslav government. It had
wide-range contacts with both Serbian government and opposition
parties to find out truth over the political crisis in Serbia, and
submitted a report to the OSCE chairman last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Tomic said the report stated three key facts: that the election
law in Yugoslavia and Serbia was coordinated with the OSCE
principles, that the victory of the leftist coalition at the
November elections was undisputable and that the opposition had
won the majority of votes in several towns and several town
municipalities.
</P>
<P>
The Serbian government annulled the local election results,
prompting the opposition, which claimed victory in the elections,
to hold daily demonstrations and protests in Belgrade and other
major cities over the past 40 days.
</P>
<P>
Tomic described as useful an initiative to hold a panel
discussion on the current political situation at the Republican
parliament, which would be broadcast live by Serbian radio and tv
and said that it would be natural for all Serbian parliamentary
parties to participate in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"This is the only true way, because everything else is not
good, everything else is not what we urge, and that is democracy
and the promotion of the multi-party life," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Serbian parliament has worked for more than a year in the
absence of a number of opposition parties, which walked out
because the national television stopped broadcasting the sessions
live, Tomic explained.
</P>
<P>
However, this was only the excuse of the opposition for not
participating in parliament's work, he said. If parties sincerely
wish to fight for their programs, they can achieve this in
parliament instead of boycotting the parliament sessions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
