<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslav President Delivers National New Year Message </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav President Zoran
Lilic said Sunday his country's aims in 1997 were peaceful
economic prosperity, promotion of democracy, state of law, human
rights, and equal relations with the international community.
</P>
<P>
In the New Year's message to the nation, issued by the
presidential office, Lilic said peace in the neighborhood and the
lifting of the sanctions was not a gift from the other countries
but "fruit of our consistent peaceful policy, of which Yugoslavia
is a guarantor, and our pledge to the stabilization of political
circumstances in the Balkans and Europe and their overall
development."
</P>
<P>
Individual and group interests must never come above the
interests of the entire nation, above the reinforcement of a state
that has just emerged from a period of unseen foreign pressures,
said Lilic.
</P>
<P>
The president said Yugoslavia needed stable internal and
foreign conditions in order to work for economic recovery and
better living to row into a real national movement.
</P>
<P>
"Over the past month, political questions and differences in
opinion can be resolved successfully only where they are resolved
in all democratic, parliamentary and multi-party states -- in
institutions set up by the will of the people," he said, referring
to the opposition demonstrations in Belgrade and other major
cities throughout Serbia.
</P>
<P>
Opposition coalition Zajedno has staged protest rallies in the
past 40 days over the annulment of results of local elections in
which the opposition has claimed victory in most big cities in
Serbia, causing political crisis in the country.
</P>
<P>
The president stressed that state organs had to execute their
constitutional and legal obligations more efficiently and without
delay.
</P>
<P>
"Whoever fails to do so must bear the consequences. It is the
right of the citizens of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia to
live in a state without street and economic crime, and without
blackmail and corruption."
</P>
<P>
Lilic said it was imperative to democratically implement the
political program for peace, unity, economic recovery, social
justice, independence and equal inclusion into European and world
integration processes.
</P>
<P>
"There is enough room for everyone in such a Yugoslavia, for
members of all nations and national minorities, all religions,
political parties," Lilic said in the end of the message. 
</P>
</TEXT>
